acceptability_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The plan review criterion for assessing whether the contemplated course of action is proportional, worth the cost, consistent with the law of war, and is militarily and politically supportable.

accompanying supplies_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Unit supplies that deploy with forces.

acoustic intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Intelligence derived from the collection and processing of acoustic phenomena.

action phase_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the period of time between the arrival of the landing forces of the amphibious force in the operational area and the accomplishment of their mission.

active defense_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The employment of limited offensive action and counterattacks to deny a contested area or position to the enemy.

active duty for training_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: A tour of active duty that is used for training members of the Reserve Component to provide trained units and qualified persons to fill the needs of the Armed Forces of the United States in time of war or national emergency and such other times as the national security requires.

activity_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A unit, organization, or installation performing a function or mission. 2. A function, mission, action, or collection of actions.

act of mercy_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In personnel recovery, assistance rendered to evaders by an individual or elements of the local population who sympathize or empathize with the evaders' cause or plight.

acute radiation syndrome_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: An acute illness caused by irradiation of the body by a high dose of penetrating radiation in a very short period of time.

ARS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An acute illness caused by irradiation of the body by a high dose of penetrating radiation in a very short period of time.

administrative contracting officer_|_dod.paragraph: Contracting officer whose primary duties involve contract administration.

ACO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Contracting officer whose primary duties involve contract administration.

administrative loading_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A loading method that gives primary consideration to achieving maximum utilization of troop and cargo space without regard to tactical considerations.

commercial loading_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A loading method that gives primary consideration to achieving maximum utilization of troop and cargo space without regard to tactical considerations.

adversary template_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A model based on an adversary's known or postulated preferred methods of operation illustrating the disposition and activity of adversary forces and assets conducting a particular operation unconstrained by the impact of the operational environment.

aeromedical evacuation_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: The movement of patients under medical supervision to and between medical treatment facilities by air transportation.

AE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The movement of patients under medical supervision to and between medical treatment facilities by air transportation.

AE_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the element of a force comprised of tailored units and aircraft assigned to conduct the initial assault on the operational area.

aerospace defense_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Defensive measures designed to destroy or nullify attacking enemy aircraft and missiles and also negate hostile space systems.

afloat pre-positioning operations_|_dod_.paragraph: Pre-positioning of ships, preloaded with equipment and supplies that provides for an alternative to land-based programs.

agent_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In intelligence usage, one who is authorized or instructed to obtain or to assist in obtaining information for intelligence or counterintelligence purposes.

air and missile defense_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: Direct [active and passive] defensive actions taken to destroy, nullify, or reduce the effectiveness of hostile air and ballistic missile threats against friendly forces and assets.

AMD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Direct [active and passive] defensive actions taken to destroy, nullify, or reduce the effectiveness of hostile air and ballistic missile threats against friendly forces and assets.

AMD_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: Located in the joint air operations center to plan, coordinate, task, and execute the air mobility mission consisting of the air mobility control team, airlift control team, air refueling control team, and aeromedical evacuation control team.

air assault_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The movement of friendly assault forces by rotary-wing or tiltrotor aircraft to engage and destroy enemy forces or to seize and hold key terrain..

air assault operation_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: An operation in which assault forces, using the mobility of rotary-wing or tiltrotor aircraft and the total integration of available fires, maneuver under the control of a ground or air maneuver commander to engage enemy forces or to seize and hold key terrain.

airborne alert_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A state of aircraft readiness wherein combat-equipped aircraft are airborne and ready for immediate action to reduce reaction time and to increase survivability.

airborne early warning_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: The detection of enemy air or surface units by radar or other equipment carried in an airborne vehicle, and the transmitting of a warning to friendly units.

airborne operation_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An operation involving the air movement into an objective area of combat forces and their logistic support for execution of a tactical, operational, or strategic mission.

aircraft carrier_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A warship designed to support and operate aircraft, engage in attacks on targets afloat or ashore, and engage in sustained operations in support of other forces.

air defense area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. overseas - A specifically defined airspace for which air defense must be planned and provided. 2. United States - Airspace of defined dimensions designated by the appropriate agency within which the ready control of airborne vehicles is required in the interest of national security during an air defense emergency.

air defense identification zone_|_dod_di.paragraph: Airspace of defined dimensions within which the ready identification, location, and control of airborne vehicles are required.

air defense sector_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A geographical subdivision of an air defense region.

air domain_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The atmosphere, beginning at the Earth's surface, extending to the altitude where its effects upon operations become negligible.

air expeditionary task force_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: A deployed numbered air force or command echelon immediately subordinate to a numbered air force provided as the United States Air Force component command committed to a joint operation.

AETF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A deployed numbered air force or command echelon immediately subordinate to a numbered air force provided as the United States Air Force component command committed to a joint operation.

Air Force special operations forces_|_do.paragraph: Those Active Component and Reserve Component Air Force forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

AFSOF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Those Active Component and Reserve Component Air Force forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

airhead line_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A line denoting the limits of the objective area for an airborne assault.

airland_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Move by air and disembark, or unload, after the aircraft has landed or while an aircraft is hovering.

air liaison officer_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The senior tactical air control party member attached to a ground unit who functions as the primary advisor to the ground commander on air power.

ALO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The senior tactical air control party member attached to a ground unit who functions as the primary advisor to the ground commander on air power.

airlift control team_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A core team within the joint air operations center with intratheater airlift functional expertise to plan, coordinate, manage, and execute intratheater airlift operations in support of the joint force air component commander.

ALCT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A core team within the joint air operations center with intratheater airlift functional expertise to plan, coordinate, manage, and execute intratheater airlift operations in support of the joint force air component commander.

airlift requirement_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The total number of passengers and/or weight/cubic displacement of cargo required to be carried by air for a specific task.

Air Mobility Command_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The Air Force component command of the United States Transportation Command.

AMC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The Air Force component command of the United States Transportation Command.

air mobility division_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Located in the joint air operations center to plan, coordinate, task, and execute the air mobility mission consisting of the air mobility control team, airlift control team, air refueling control team, and aeromedical evacuation control team.

air movement_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Air transport of units, personnel, supplies, and equipment, including airdrops and air landings.

air refueling_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The refueling of an aircraft in flight by another aircraft.

AR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The refueling of an aircraft in flight by another aircraft.

air route_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The navigable airspace between two points, identified to the extent necessary for the application of flight rules.

airspace control_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Capabilities and procedures used to increase operational effectiveness by promoting the safe, efficient, and flexible use of airspace.

airspace control authority_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The commander designated to assume overall responsibility for the operation of the airspace control system in the airspace control area.

ACA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The commander designated to assume overall responsibility for the operation of the airspace control system in the airspace control area.

ACA_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: A three-dimensional block of airspace in a target area, established by the appropriate commander, in which friendly aircraft are reasonably safe from friendly surface fires.

airspace control plan_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The document approved by the joint force commander that provides specific planning guidance and procedures for the airspace control system for the joint force operational area.

ACP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The document approved by the joint force commander that provides specific planning guidance and procedures for the airspace control system for the joint force operational area.

airspace control system_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: An arrangement of those organizations, personnel, policies, procedures, and facilities required to perform airspace control functions.

ACS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An arrangement of those organizations, personnel, policies, procedures, and facilities required to perform airspace control functions.

airspace coordination area_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A three-dimensional block of airspace in a target area, established by the appropriate commander, in which friendly aircraft are reasonably safe from friendly surface fires.

air superiority_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That degree of control of the air by one force that permits the conduct of its operations at a given time and place without prohibitive interference from air and missile threats.

air support operations center_|_dod_dict.paragraph: The principal air control agency of the theater air control system responsible for the direction and control of air operations directly supporting the ground combat element.

ASOC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The principal air control agency of the theater air control system responsible for the direction and control of air operations directly supporting the ground combat element.

air supremacy_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That degree of control of the air wherein the opposing force is incapable of effective interference within the operational area using air and missile threats.

air terminal_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A facility on an airfield that functions as an air transportation hub and accommodates the loading and unloading of airlift aircraft and the in-transit processing of traffic.

alert order_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A planning directive normally associated with a crisis, issued by the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, on behalf of the President or Secretary of Defense, that provides essential planning guidance and directs the development, adaptation, or refinement of a plan/order after the directing authority approves a military course of action. 2. A planning directive that provides essential planning guidance, directs the initiation of planning after the directing authority approves a military course of action, but does not authorize execution.

ALERTORD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A planning directive normally associated with a crisis, issued by the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, on behalf of the President or Secretary of Defense, that provides essential planning guidance and directs the development, adaptation, or refinement of a plan/order after the directing authority approves a military course of action. 2. A planning directive that provides essential planning guidance, directs the initiation of planning after the directing authority approves a military course of action, but does not authorize execution.

Allied System for Geospatial Intelligenc.paragraph: A partnership between five nations (United States and allied partners Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom) to advance the geospatial intelligence mission with a common analytic environment to provide a common geospatial intelligence picture.

ASG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A partnership between five nations (United States and allied partners Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom) to advance the geospatial intelligence mission with a common analytic environment to provide a common geospatial intelligence picture.

allowable cabin load_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The maximum payload that can be carried on an individual sortie.

ACL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The maximum payload that can be carried on an individual sortie.

amphibian_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A small craft, propelled by propellers and wheels or by air cushions for the purpose of moving on both land and water.

amphibious air traffic control center_|_.paragraph: The centralized air traffic control agency on an amphibious warfare ship responsible for operational control of aircraft departing from and recovering on the ship and tactical control of airborne helicopters in support of amphibious assaults.

AATCC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The centralized air traffic control agency on an amphibious warfare ship responsible for operational control of aircraft departing from and recovering on the ship and tactical control of airborne helicopters in support of amphibious assaults.

amphibious assault vehicle launching are.paragraph: An area, in the vicinity of and to seaward of the line of departure, to which landing ships proceed and launch amphibious assault vehicles.

amphibious bulk liquid transfer system_|.paragraph: Hose-reel system providing capability to deliver fuel and/or water from ship to shore.

ABLTS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Hose-reel system providing capability to deliver fuel and/or water from ship to shore.

amphibious defense zone_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The area encompassing the amphibious objective area and the adjoining airspace required by accompanying naval forces for the purpose of air defense.

an ADZ_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The area encompassing the amphibious objective area and the adjoining airspace required by accompanying naval forces for the purpose of air defense.

amphibious force_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An amphibious task force and a landing force together with other forces that are trained, organized, and equipped for amphibious operations.

AF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An amphibious task force and a landing force together with other forces that are trained, organized, and equipped for amphibious operations.

amphibious operation_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A military operation launched from the sea by an amphibious force to conduct landing force operations within the littorals.

PHIBOP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A military operation launched from the sea by an amphibious force to conduct landing force operations within the littorals.

amphibious ready group_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A Navy task organization formed to conduct amphibious operations, commanded by an amphibious squadron commander.

ARG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Navy task organization formed to conduct amphibious operations, commanded by an amphibious squadron commander.

amphibious task force_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A Navy task organization formed to conduct amphibious operations.

ATF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Navy task organization formed to conduct amphibious operations.

amphibious vehicle availability table_|_.paragraph: A tabulation of the type and number of amphibious vehicles available primarily for assault landings and for support of other elements of the operation.

amphibious warfare ship_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A combatant ship having organic capability to embark, land, and support landing forces in amphibious operations and which has characteristics enabling long-duration operations on the high seas.

analysis and production_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: In intelligence usage, the conversion of processed information into intelligence through the integration, evaluation, analysis, and interpretation of all source data and the preparation of intelligence products in support of known or anticipated user requirements.

Antideficiency Act violations_|_dod_dict.paragraph: The incurring of obligations or the making of expenditure (outlays) in violation of appropriation law as to purpose, time, and amounts as specified in the defense appropriation or appropriations of funds.

antisubmarine warfare_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Operations conducted with the intention of denying the enemy the effective use of submarines.

ASW_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Operations conducted with the intention of denying the enemy the effective use of submarines.

anti-vehicle land mine_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A mine designed to immobilize or destroy a vehicle.

AVL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A mine designed to immobilize or destroy a vehicle.

apportionment_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The quantities of force capabilities and resources provided for planning purposes only, but not necessarily an identification of the actual forces that may be allocated for use when a plan transitions to execution.

apron_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A defined area on an airfield intended to accommodate aircraft for purposes of loading or unloading passengers or cargo, refueling, parking, or maintenance.

area damage control_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Measures taken before, during, and/or after a hostile action or natural or manmade disasters to reduce the probability of damage and minimize its effects.

ADC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Measures taken before, during, and/or after a hostile action or natural or manmade disasters to reduce the probability of damage and minimize its effects.

area of influence_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A geographical area wherein a commander is directly capable of influencing operations by maneuver or fire support systems normally under the commander's command or control.

area of operations_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An operational area defined by a commander for land and maritime forces that should be large enough to accomplish their missions and protect their forces.

AO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An operational area defined by a commander for land and maritime forces that should be large enough to accomplish their missions and protect their forces.

area search_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Visual reconnaissance of limited or defined areas.

arming_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: As applied to explosives, weapons, and ammunition, the changing from a safe condition to a state of readiness for initiation.

Army corps_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An echelon of command and tactical formations that employs divisions, multifunctional brigades, and functional brigades to achieve objectives on land.

Army Service component command_|_dod_dic.paragraph: Command responsible for recommendations to the joint force commander on the allocation and employment of Army forces within a combatant command.

ASCC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Command responsible for recommendations to the joint force commander on the allocation and employment of Army forces within a combatant command.

Army support area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: At all echelons, an area designated to facilitate the positioning, employment, and protection of sustainment assets; and where the majority of sustaining operations occur.

ascent phase_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That portion of the flight of a ballistic missile or space vehicle that begins after powered flight and ends just prior to apogee.

assault breaching_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A part of amphibious breaching in support of an amphibious assault involving a fire support mission using precision-guided munitions to neutralize mines and obstacles in the surf zone and on the beach.

assault echelon_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the element of a force comprised of tailored units and aircraft assigned to conduct the initial assault on the operational area.

assault phase_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In an airborne operation, a phase beginning with delivery by air of the assault echelon of the force into the objective area and extending through attack of assault objectives and consolidation of the initial airhead.

assessment_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A continuous process that measures the overall effectiveness of employing capabilities during military operations. 2. Determination of the progress toward accomplishing a task, creating a condition, or achieving an objective. 3. Analysis of the security, effectiveness, and potential of an existing or planned intelligence activity. 4. Judgment of the motives, qualifications, and characteristics of present or prospective employees or "agents."

asset validation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In intelligence use, the process used to determine the asset authenticity, reliability, utility, suitability, and degree of control the case officer or others have.

assign_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. To place units or personnel in an organization where such placement is relatively permanent, and/or where such organization controls and administers the units or personnel for the primary function, or greater portion of the functions, of the unit or personnel. 2. To detail individuals to specific duties or functions where such duties or functions are primary and/or relatively permanent.

atmospheric environment_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The envelope of air surrounding the Earth, including its interfaces and interactions with the Earth's solid or liquid surface.

attack group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A subordinate task organization of the Navy forces of an amphibious task force composed of amphibious warfare ships and supporting naval units designated to transport, protect, land, and initially support a landing group.

attack position_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The last position occupied by the assault echelon before crossing the line of departure.

authentication_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A security measure designed to protect a communications system against acceptance of a fraudulent transmission or simulation by establishing the validity of a transmission, message, or originator. 2. A means of identifying individuals and verifying their eligibility to receive specific categories of information. 3. Evidence by proper signature or seal that a document is genuine and official. 4. In personnel recovery missions, the process whereby the identity of an isolated person is confirmed.

Automated Repatriation Reporting System_.paragraph: A Defense Manpower Data Center system used to track the status of noncombatant evacuees after they have arrived in an initial safe haven in the United States.

autonomous operation_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: In air defense, the mode of operation assumed by a unit after it has lost all communications with higher echelons forcing the unit commander to assume full responsibility for control of weapons and engagement of hostile targets.

aviation medicine_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The special field of medicine that is related to the biological and psychological problems of flight. (JP 4-02) B

bale cubic capacity_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The space available for cargo measured in cubic feet to the inside of the cargo battens, on the frames, and to the underside of the beams.

barrier_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A coordinated series of natural or man-made obstacles designed or employed to channel, direct, restrict, delay, or stop the movement of an opposing force and to impose additional losses in personnel, time, and equipment on the opposing force.

barrier, obstacle, and mine warfare plan.query: barrier, obstacle, and mine warfare plan
barrier, obstacle, and mine warfare plan.paragraph: A comprehensive, coordinated plan that includes responsibilities; general location of unspecified and specific barriers, obstacles, and minefields; special instructions; limitations; coordination; and completion times; and may designate locations of obstacle zones or belts.

base boundary_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A line that delineates the surface area of a base for the purpose of facilitating coordination and deconfliction of operations between adjacent units, formations, or areas. (JP 3-10) base cluster -A collection of bases, geographically grouped for mutual protection and ease of command and control.

base defense operations center_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A command and control facility established by the base commander to serve as the focal point for base security and defense.

BDOC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A command and control facility established by the base commander to serve as the focal point for base security and defense.

base development_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The acquisition, development, expansion, improvement, construction and/or replacement of the facilities and resources of a location to support forces.

base operating support_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Directly assisting, maintaining, supplying, and distributing support of forces at the operating location.

BOS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Directly assisting, maintaining, supplying, and distributing support of forces at the operating location.

base plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A type of operation plan that describes the concept of operations, major forces, sustainment concept, and anticipated timelines for completing the mission without annexes or time-phased force and deployment data.

BPLAN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A type of operation plan that describes the concept of operations, major forces, sustainment concept, and anticipated timelines for completing the mission without annexes or time-phased force and deployment data.

basic encyclopedia_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A compilation of identified installations and physical areas of potential significance as objectives for attack.

battalion landing team_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: 1. In an amphibious operation, an infantry battalion normally reinforced by necessary combat and service elements. 2. The basic unit for planning an assault landing.

BLT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In an amphibious operation, an infantry battalion normally reinforced by necessary combat and service elements. 2. The basic unit for planning an assault landing.

battle damage repair_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: Essential repair, which may be improvised, carried out rapidly in a hostile environment in order to return damaged or disabled equipment to temporary service.

battle injury_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Damage or harm sustained by personnel during or as a result of battle conditions.

BI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Damage or harm sustained by personnel during or as a result of battle conditions.

battle rhythm_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A deliberate, daily schedule of command, staff, and unit activities intended to maximize use of time and synchronize staff actions.

beachhead_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A designated area on a hostile or potentially hostile shore that, when seized and held, ensures the continuous landing of troops and materiel and provides maneuver space requisite for subsequent projected operations ashore.

beach party_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The Navy component of the landing force support party under the tactical control of the landing force support party commander.

begin morning civil twilight_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: The period of time at which the sun is halfway between beginning morning and nautical twilight and sunrise, when there is enough light to see objects clearly with the unaided eye.

biological agent_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A microorganism (or a toxin derived from it) that causes disease in personnel, plants, or animals or causes the deterioration of materiel.

biometrics_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of recognizing an individual based on measurable anatomical, physiological, and behavioral characteristics.

biosurveillance_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process to gather, integrate, interpret, and communicate essential information related to all-hazards, threats, or disease activity affecting human, animal, or plant health to achieve early detection and warning, contribute to overall situational awareness of the health aspects of an incident, and to enable better decision making at all levels.

blood agent_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A chemical compound, including the cyanide group, that affects bodily functions by preventing the normal utilization of oxygen by body tissues.

board_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organized group of individuals within a headquarters, appointed and tasked by the commander (or other authority), that meets with the purpose of gaining guidance or decision.

boat lane_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A lane for amphibious assault landing craft, which extends from the line of departure to the beach.

bona fides_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In personnel recovery, the use of verbal or visual communication by individuals who are unknown to one another, to establish their authenticity, sincerity, honesty, and truthfulness.

bottom mine_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A mine with negative buoyancy that remains on the seabed.

branch_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A subdivision of any organization. 2. A geographically separate unit of an activity, which performs all or part of the primary functions of the parent activity on a smaller scale. 3. An arm or service of the Army. 4. The contingency options built into the base plan used for changing the mission, orientation, or direction of movement of a force to aid success of the operation based on anticipated events, opportunities, or disruptions caused by enemy actions and reactions.

brevity code_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A code word, which provides no security, that serves the sole purpose of shortening of messages rather than the concealment of their content.

broken stowage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The space lost in the holds of a vessel because of the contour of the ship, dunnage, ladders, stanchions, and the shape of the cargo.

buddy aid_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Acute medical care (first aid) provided by a nonmedical Service member to another person.

building system_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A structure assembled from manufactured components designed to provide a specific building configuration.

bulk petroleum product_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A liquid petroleum product transported by various means and stored in tanks or containers having an individual fill capacity greater than 208 liters.

cache_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A source of subsistence and supplies, typically containing items such as food, water, medical items, and/or communications equipment, packaged to prevent damage from exposure and hidden in isolated locations by such methods as burial, concealment, and/or submersion, to support isolated personnel.

campaign_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A series of related operations aimed at achieving strategic and operational objectives within a given time and space.

canalize_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: To restrict operations to a narrow zone by use of existing or reinforcing obstacles or by fire or bombing.

capstone joint publication_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The top joint publication in the hierarchy of joint publications that links joint doctrine to national strategy and the contributions of other United States Government departments and agencies, multinational partners, and reinforces policy for command and control.

carrier air wing_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Two or more aircraft squadrons formed under one commander for administrative and tactical control of operations from a carrier.

CVW_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Two or more aircraft squadrons formed under one commander for administrative and tactical control of operations from a carrier.

carrier strike group_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A standing naval task group consisting of a carrier, embarked air wing, surface combatants, and submarines as assigned in direct support, operating in mutual support with the task of destroying hostile submarine, surface, and air forces within the group's assigned operational area and striking at targets along hostile shore lines or projecting power inland.

CSG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A standing naval task group consisting of a carrier, embarked air wing, surface combatants, and submarines as assigned in direct support, operating in mutual support with the task of destroying hostile submarine, surface, and air forces within the group's assigned operational area and striking at targets along hostile shore lines or projecting power inland.

case officer_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A professional employee of an intelligence or counterintelligence organization, who provides directions for an agent operation and/or handling intelligence assets.

casualty evacuation_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The unregulated movement of casualties that can include movement both to and between medical treatment facilities.

CASEVAC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The unregulated movement of casualties that can include movement both to and between medical treatment facilities.

casualty receiving and treatment ship_|_.paragraph: In amphibious operations, a ship designated to receive, provide treatment for, and transfer casualties.

CRTS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, a ship designated to receive, provide treatment for, and transfer casualties.

causeway_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A craft similar in design to a barge, but longer and narrower, designed to assist in the discharge and transport of cargo from vessels.

C-day_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The unnamed day on which a deployment operation commences or is to commence.

center_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An enduring, functional organization, with a supporting staff, designed to perform a joint function within a headquarters.

central control officer_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The officer, embarked in the central control ship, designated by the amphibious task force commander for the overall coordination of the waterborne ship-to-shore movement.

CCO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The officer, embarked in the central control ship, designated by the amphibious task force commander for the overall coordination of the waterborne ship-to-shore movement.

chaff_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Radar confusion reflectors, consisting of thin, narrow metallic strips of various lengths and frequency responses, which are used to reflect echoes for confusion purposes.

Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in.query: Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff instruction
Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in.paragraph: A document containing Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff policy that does not involve the employment of forces and is applicable to the Joint Staff, Services, National Guard Bureau, defense agencies, and combatant commands and may be informational to other agencies.

CJCSI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A document containing Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff policy that does not involve the employment of forces and is applicable to the Joint Staff, Services, National Guard Bureau, defense agencies, and combatant commands and may be informational to other agencies.

chalk number_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The number given to a complete load and to the transporting carrier.

channel airlift_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Airlift provided for movement of sustainment cargo, scheduled either regularly or depending upon volume of workload, between designated ports of embarkation and ports of debarkation over validated contingency or distribution routes.

chemical, biological, radiological, and.query: chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense
chemical, biological, radiological, and.paragraph: Measures taken to minimize or negate the vulnerabilities to, and/or effects of, a chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear hazard or incident.

CBRN defense_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Measures taken to minimize or negate the vulnerabilities to, and/or effects of, a chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear hazard or incident.

chemical, biological, radiological, and.query: chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear hazard
chemical, biological, radiological, and.paragraph: Chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear elements that could create adverse effects due to an accidental or deliberate release and dissemination.

CBRN hazard_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear elements that could create adverse effects due to an accidental or deliberate release and dissemination.

chemical, biological, radiological, or n.query: chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear incident
chemical, biological, radiological, or n.paragraph: Any occurrence, resulting from the use of chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear weapons and devices; the emergence of secondary hazards arising from friendly actions; or the release of toxic industrial materials or biological organisms and substances into the environment, involving the emergence of chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear hazards.

chemical warfare_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All aspects of military operations involving the employment of lethal and incapacitating chemical munitions/agents and the warning and protective measures associated with such offensive operations.

CW_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All aspects of military operations involving the employment of lethal and incapacitating chemical munitions/agents and the warning and protective measures associated with such offensive operations.

chief of fires_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The senior organic fires Army staff officer at division and higher headquarters level who advises the commander on the best use of available fire support resources, provides input to necessary orders, and develops and implements the fire support plan.

chief of staff_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The senior or principal member or head of a staff who acts as the controlling member of a staff for purposes of the coordination of its work or to exercise command in another's name.

COS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The senior or principal member or head of a staff who acts as the controlling member of a staff for purposes of the coordination of its work or to exercise command in another's name.

civil affairs_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Designated Active Component and Reserve Component forces and units organized, trained, and equipped specifically to conduct civil affairs operations and to support civil-military operations.

CA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Designated Active Component and Reserve Component forces and units organized, trained, and equipped specifically to conduct civil affairs operations and to support civil-military operations.

CA_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: An airspace coordinating measure that uses altitude to separate users and as the transition between different airspace control elements.

civil augmentation program_|_dod_diction.paragraph: Standing, long-term external support contracts designed to augment Service logistics capabilities with contracted support in both preplanned and short-notice contingencies.

CAP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Standing, long-term external support contracts designed to augment Service logistics capabilities with contracted support in both preplanned and short-notice contingencies.

CAP_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: An aircraft patrol provided over an objective area, the force protected, the critical area of a combat zone, or in an air defense area, for the purpose of intercepting and destroying hostile aircraft before they reach their targets.

civil authority information support_|_do.paragraph: The use of military information support operations capabilities to conduct public information dissemination activities to support national security or disaster relief operations within the United States and its territories in support of a lead federal agency.

CAIS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The use of military information support operations capabilities to conduct public information dissemination activities to support national security or disaster relief operations within the United States and its territories in support of a lead federal agency.

civil information_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Relevant data relating to the civil areas, structures, capabilities, organizations, people, and events of the civil component of the operational environment used to support the situational awareness of the supported commander.

civil-military medicine_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A discipline within operational medicine comprising public health and medical issues that involve a civil-military interface (foreign or domestic), including medical defense support of civil authorities, medical elements of security cooperation activities, and medical civil-military operations.

civil-military operations center_|_dod_d.paragraph: An organization, normally comprised of civil affairs, established to plan and facilitate coordination of activities of the Armed Forces of the United States within indigenous populations and institutions, the private sector, international organizations, nongovernmental organizations, multinational forces, and other governmental agencies in support of the commander.

CMOC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organization, normally comprised of civil affairs, established to plan and facilitate coordination of activities of the Armed Forces of the United States within indigenous populations and institutions, the private sector, international organizations, nongovernmental organizations, multinational forces, and other governmental agencies in support of the commander.

civil reconnaissance_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A targeted, planned, and coordinated observation and evaluation of specific civil aspects of the environment such as areas, structures, capabilities, organizations, people, or events.

CR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A targeted, planned, and coordinated observation and evaluation of specific civil aspects of the environment such as areas, structures, capabilities, organizations, people, or events.

civil search and rescue_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: Search and/or rescue operations and associated civilian services provided to assist persons in potential or actual distress and protect property in a nonhostile environment.

civil SAR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Search and/or rescue operations and associated civilian services provided to assist persons in potential or actual distress and protect property in a nonhostile environment.

clandestine operation_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: An operation sponsored or conducted by governmental departments or agencies in such a way as to assure secrecy or concealment.

classification_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The determination that official information requires, in the interests of national security, a specific degree of protection against unauthorized disclosure, coupled with a designation signifying that such a determination has been made.

clearance capacity_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An estimate expressed in agreed upon units of cargo measurement per day of the cargo or people that may be transported inland from a beach or port over the available means of inland communication, including roads, railroads, airlift, and inland waterways.

clearing operation_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An operation designed to clear or neutralize all mines and obstacles from a route or area.

close air support_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Air action by aircraft against hostile targets that are in close proximity to friendly forces and that require detailed integration of each air mission with the fire and movement of those forces.

CAS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Air action by aircraft against hostile targets that are in close proximity to friendly forces and that require detailed integration of each air mission with the fire and movement of those forces.

close support_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The action of the supporting force against targets or objectives that are sufficiently near the supported force as to require detailed integration or coordination of the supporting action.

closure_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In transportation, the process of a unit's arriving at a specified location.

collateral damage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A form of collateral effect that causes unintentional or incidental injury or damage to persons or objects that would not be lawful military targets in the circumstances ruling at the time.

collection_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In intelligence usage, the acquisition of information and the provision of this information to processing elements.

collection asset_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A collection system, platform, or capability that is supporting, assigned, or attached to a particular commander.

collection manager_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An individual with responsibility for the timely and efficient tasking of organic collection resources and the development of requirements for theater and national assets that could satisfy specific information needs in support of the mission.

CM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An individual with responsibility for the timely and efficient tasking of organic collection resources and the development of requirements for theater and national assets that could satisfy specific information needs in support of the mission.

collection plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A systematic scheme to optimize the employment of all available collection capabilities and associated processing, exploitation, and dissemination resources to satisfy specific information requirements. See also information requirements; intelligence process.

collection posture_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The current status of collection assets and resources to satisfy identified information requirements.

collection requirements management_|_dod.paragraph: The authoritative development and control of collection, processing, exploitation, and/or reporting requirements that normally result in either the direct tasking of requirements to units over which the commander has authority, or the generation of tasking requests to collection management authorities at a higher, lower, or lateral echelon to accomplish the collection mission.

CRM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The authoritative development and control of collection, processing, exploitation, and/or reporting requirements that normally result in either the direct tasking of requirements to units over which the commander has authority, or the generation of tasking requests to collection management authorities at a higher, lower, or lateral echelon to accomplish the collection mission.

collection resource_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A collection system, platform, or capability that is not supporting, assigned, or attached to a specific unit or echelon which must be requested and coordinated through the chain of command.

collective protection_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The protection provided to a group of individuals that permits relaxation of individual chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear protection.

COLPRO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The protection provided to a group of individuals that permits relaxation of individual chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear protection.

combat air patrol_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An aircraft patrol provided over an objective area, the force protected, the critical area of a combat zone, or in an air defense area, for the purpose of intercepting and destroying hostile aircraft before they reach their targets.

combat and operational stress control_|_.paragraph: Programs developed and actions taken by military leadership to prevent, identify, and manage adverse combat and operational stress reactions in units; optimize mission performance; conserve fighting strength; prevent or minimize adverse effects of combat and operational stress on members' physical, psychological, intellectual, and social health; and to return the unit or Service member to duty expeditiously.

COSC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Programs developed and actions taken by military leadership to prevent, identify, and manage adverse combat and operational stress reactions in units; optimize mission performance; conserve fighting strength; prevent or minimize adverse effects of combat and operational stress on members' physical, psychological, intellectual, and social health; and to return the unit or Service member to duty expeditiously.

combatant command chaplain_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The senior chaplain assigned to the staff of, or designated by, the combatant commander to provide advice on religion, ethical, and moral issues and morale of assigned personnel and to coordinate religious ministries within the combatant commander's area of responsibility.

combatant commander_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A commander of one of the unified or specified combatant commands established by the President.

CCDR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A commander of one of the unified or specified combatant commands established by the President.

combatant command support agent_|_dod_di.paragraph: The Secretary of a Military Department to whom the Secretary of Defense or the Deputy Secretary of Defense has assigned administrative and logistical support of the headquarters of a combatant command, United States Element, North American Aerospace Defense Command, or subordinate unified command. The nature and scope of the combatant command support agent responsibilities, functions, and authorities shall be prescribed at the time of assignment or in keeping with existing agreements and practices, and they shall remain in effect until the Secretary of Defense or the Deputy Secretary of Defense revokes, supersedes, or modifies them.

combat camera_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Specially-trained expeditionary forces from Service-designated units capable of providing high-quality directed visual information during military operations.

COMCAM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Specially-trained expeditionary forces from Service-designated units capable of providing high-quality directed visual information during military operations.

combat control team_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A task-organized team of special operations forces who are certified air traffic controllers that are trained and equipped to deploy into hostile environments to establish and control assault zones and airfields.

combat identification_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The process of attaining an accurate characterization of detected objects in the operational environment sufficient to support an engagement decision.

CID_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of attaining an accurate characterization of detected objects in the operational environment sufficient to support an engagement decision.

combat lifesaver_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Nonmedical Department of Defense person who has received additional trauma training and equipment, providing enhanced medical treatment beyond self-aid/buddy aid.

combat organizational loading_|_dod_dict.paragraph: A method of loading by which a unit with its equipment and initial supplies is loaded into a single ship, together with other units, in such a manner as to be available for unloading in a predetermined order.

combat search and rescue_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The tactics, techniques, and procedures performed by forces to effect the recovery of isolated personnel during combat.

CSAR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The tactics, techniques, and procedures performed by forces to effect the recovery of isolated personnel during combat.

combat service support area_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: An area ashore that is organized to contain the necessary supplies, equipment, installations, and elements to provide the landing force with combat service support throughout the operation.

CSSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An area ashore that is organized to contain the necessary supplies, equipment, installations, and elements to provide the landing force with combat service support throughout the operation.

combat support_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire support and operational assistance provided to combat elements.

CS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire support and operational assistance provided to combat elements.

combat surveillance_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A continuous, all-weather, day-and-night, systematic watch over the battle area in order to provide timely information for tactical combat operations.

combined_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A term identifying two or more forces or agencies of two or more allies operating together.

command_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The authority that a commander in the armed forces lawfully exercises over subordinates by virtue of rank or assignment. 2. An order given by a commander; that is, the will of the commander expressed for the purpose of bringing about a particular action. 3. A unit or units, an organization, or an area under the command of one individual.

command and control system_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The facilities, equipment, communications, procedures, and personnel essential for a commander to plan, direct, and control operations of forces pursuant to the missions assigned.

commander, amphibious task force_|_dod_d.paragraph: The Navy officer designated in the initiating directive as the commander of the amphibious task force. Also called CATF. See also amphibious operation; amphibious task force; commander, landing force.

commander's communication synchronizatio.paragraph: A process to coordinate and synchronize narratives, themes, messages, images, operations, and actions to ensure their integrity and consistency to the lowest tactical level across all relevant communication activities.

CCS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A process to coordinate and synchronize narratives, themes, messages, images, operations, and actions to ensure their integrity and consistency to the lowest tactical level across all relevant communication activities.

commander's estimate_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The commander's initial assessment in which options are provided in a concise statement that defines who, what, when, where, why, and how the course of action will be implemented.

commander's required delivery date_|_dod.paragraph: The original date relative to C-day, specified by the combatant commander for arrival of forces or cargo at the destination; shown in the time-phased force and deployment data to assess the impact of later arrival.

commanding officer of troops_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: On a ship that has embarked units, a designated officer (usually the senior embarking unit commander) who is responsible for the administration, discipline, and training of all embarked units.

COT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: On a ship that has embarked units, a designated officer (usually the senior embarking unit commander) who is responsible for the administration, discipline, and training of all embarked units.

command relationships_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The interrelated responsibilities between commanders, as well as the operational authority exercised by commanders in the chain of command; defined further as combatant command (command authority), operational control, tactical control, or support.

commit_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of assigning one or more aircraft or surface-to-air missile units to prepare to engage an entity, prior to authorizing such engagement. (JP 3-01) commodity loading -A method of loading in which various types of cargoes are loaded together, such as ammunition, rations, or boxed vehicles, in order that each commodity can be discharged without disturbing the others.

common item_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Any item of materiel that is required for use by more than one activity. 2. A term loosely used to denote any consumable item except repair parts or other technical items. 3. Any item of materiel that is procured for, owned by (Service stock), or used by any Military Department of the Department of Defense and is also required to be furnished to a recipient country under the grant-aid Military Assistance Program. 4. Readily available commercial items. 5. Items used by two or more Military Services of similar manufacture or fabrication that may vary between the Services as to color or shape (as vehicles or clothing). 6. Any part or component that is required in the assembly of two or more complete end-items.

common operational picture_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A single identical display of relevant information shared by more than one command that facilitates collaborative planning and assists all echelons to achieve situational awareness.

COP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A single identical display of relevant information shared by more than one command that facilitates collaborative planning and assists all echelons to achieve situational awareness.

common tactical picture_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: An accurate and complete display of relevant tactical data that integrates tactical information from the multi-tactical data link network, ground network, intelligence network, and sensor networks.

CTP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An accurate and complete display of relevant tactical data that integrates tactical information from the multi-tactical data link network, ground network, intelligence network, and sensor networks.

common-user airlift service_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: The airlift service provided on a common basis for all Department of Defense agencies and, as authorized, for other agencies of the United States Government.

common-user land transportation_|_dod_di.paragraph: Point-to-point land transportation service operated by a single Service for common use by two or more Services.

CULT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Point-to-point land transportation service operated by a single Service for common use by two or more Services.

common-user ocean terminal_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A military installation, part of a military installation, or a commercial facility operated under contract or arrangement by the Military Surface Deployment and Distribution Command that regularly provides for two or more Services terminal functions of receipt, transit storage or staging, processing, and loading and unloading of passengers or cargo aboard ships.

common-user transportation_|_dod_diction.paragraph: Transportation and transportation services provided on a common basis for two or more Department of Defense agencies and, as authorized, non-Department of Defense agencies.

communications network_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An organization of stations capable of intercommunications, but not necessarily on the same channel.

COMNET_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organization of stations capable of intercommunications, but not necessarily on the same channel.

communications security material_|_dod_d.paragraph: All documents, devices, equipment, apparatus, and cryptomaterial used in establishing or maintaining secure communications.

competing observable_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: Within military deception, any observable that contradicts the deception story, casts doubt on, or diminishes the impact of one or more required or supporting observables. (JP 3-13.4) completeness -The plan review criterion for assessing whether operation plans incorporate major operations and tasks to be accomplished and to what degree they include forces required, deployment concept, employment concept, sustainment concept, time estimates for achieving objectives, description of the military end state, mission success criteria, and mission transition criteria.

component_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. One of the subordinate organizations that constitute a joint force. (JP 1) 2. In logistics, a part or combination of parts having a specific function, which can be installed or replaced only as an entity.

composite warfare commander_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: An officer to whom the officer in tactical command of a naval task organization may delegate authority to conduct some or all of the offensive and defensive functions of the force.

CWC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An officer to whom the officer in tactical command of a naval task organization may delegate authority to conduct some or all of the offensive and defensive functions of the force.

concept of intelligence operations_|_dod.paragraph: Within the Department of Defense, a verbal or graphic statement, in broad outline, of an intelligence directorate's assumptions or intent in regard to intelligence support of an operation or series of operations.

concept of operations_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A verbal or graphic statement that clearly and concisely expresses what the commander intends to accomplish and how it will be done using available resources.

CONOPS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A verbal or graphic statement that clearly and concisely expresses what the commander intends to accomplish and how it will be done using available resources.

condition_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Those variables of an operational environment or situation in which a unit, system, or individual is expected to operate and may affect performance. 2. A physical or behavioral state of a system that is required for the achievement of an objective.

configuration management_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: A discipline applying technical and administrative direction and surveillance to: (1) identify and document the functional and physical characteristics of a configuration item, (2) control changes to those characteristics, and (3) record and report changes to processing and implementation status.

consolidation area_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The portion of the land commander's operational area that may be designated to facilitate freedom of action, consolidate gains, and set conditions to transition to follow on forces or other legitimate authorities.

constraint_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In the context of planning, a requirement placed on the command by a higher command that dictates an action, thus restricting freedom of action.

consumption rate_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The average quantity of an item consumed or expended during a given time interval, expressed in quantities by the most appropriate unit of measurement per applicable stated basis.

contact point_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In land warfare, a point on the terrain, easily identifiable, where two or more units are required to make contact. (JP 3-50) 2. In air operations, the position at which a mission leader makes radio contact with an air control agency. (JP 3-09.3) 3. In personnel recovery, a location where isolated personnel can establish contact with recovery forces.

CP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In land warfare, a point on the terrain, easily identifiable, where two or more units are required to make contact. (JP 3-50) 2. In air operations, the position at which a mission leader makes radio contact with an air control agency. (JP 3-09.3) 3. In personnel recovery, a location where isolated personnel can establish contact with recovery forces.

CP_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: 1. A position along a route of march at which personnel are stationed to give information and instructions for the regulation of supply or traffic. 2. A position marked by coordinates (latitude, longitude), a buoy, boat, aircraft, electronic device, conspicuous terrain feature, or other identifiable object, which is given a name or number and used as an aid to navigation or control of ships, boats, or aircraft. 3. In marking mosaics, a point located by ground survey with which a corresponding point on a photograph is matched as a check.

container_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An article of transport equipment that meets American National Standards Institute/International Organization for Standardization standards that is designed to facilitate and optimize the carriage of goods by one or more modes of transportation without intermediate handling of the contents.

container-handling equipment_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: Items of materials-handling equipment required to specifically receive, maneuver, and dispatch International Organization for Standardization containers.

CHE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Items of materials-handling equipment required to specifically receive, maneuver, and dispatch International Organization for Standardization containers.

containership_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A ship, usually without shipboard-installed cranes for loading/off-loading containers, specially constructed and equipped to carry only containers without associated equipment, in all available cargo spaces, either below or above deck.

contamination_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The deposit, absorption, or adsorption of radioactive material or of biological or chemical agents on or by structures, areas, personnel, or objects.

fallout radiation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The deposit, absorption, or adsorption of radioactive material or of biological or chemical agents on or by structures, areas, personnel, or objects.

contamination control_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A combination of preparatory and responsive measures designed to limit the vulnerability of forces to chemical, biological, radiological, nuclear, and toxic industrial hazards and to avoid, contain, control exposure to, and, where possible, neutralize them. See also biological agent; chemical agent; contamination.

contiguous zone_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A maritime zone adjacent to the territorial sea that may not extend beyond 24 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured. 2. The zone of the ocean extending 3-12 nautical miles from the United States coastline.

contingency_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A situation requiring military operations in response to natural disasters, terrorists, subversives, or as otherwise directed by appropriate authority to protect United States interests.

contingency contract administration serv.paragraph: A subset of contingency contracting that includes efforts to ensure supplies, services, and construction are delivered in accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract through delegated contracting authority.

CCAS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A subset of contingency contracting that includes efforts to ensure supplies, services, and construction are delivered in accordance with the terms and conditions of the contract through delegated contracting authority.

contingency contracting officer_|_dod_di.paragraph: A military or emergency-essential government civilian contracting officer in a position that is intended to provide contracting services in a deployed environment.

contingency location_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A non-enduring location outside of the United States that supports and sustains operations during contingencies or other operations and is categorized by mission life-cycle requirements as initial, temporary, or semipermanent.

contingency plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A branch of a campaign plan that is planned based on hypothetical situations for designated threats, catastrophic events, and contingent missions outside of crisis conditions.

continuity of operations_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The degree or state of being continuous in the conduct of functions, tasks, or duties necessary to accomplish a military action or mission in carrying out the national military strategy.

COOP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The degree or state of being continuous in the conduct of functions, tasks, or duties necessary to accomplish a military action or mission in carrying out the national military strategy.

contracting officer's representative_|_d.paragraph: An individual designated in writing by the contracting officer to perform specific technical or administrative functions.

COR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An individual designated in writing by the contracting officer to perform specific technical or administrative functions.

contractor management_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The oversight and integration of contractor personnel and associated equipment in support of military operations.

contractors authorized to accompany the.query: contractors authorized to accompany the force
contractors authorized to accompany the.paragraph: Contractor employees and all tiers of subcontractor employees who are authorized to accompany the force in applicable contingency operations outside of the United States and have afforded such status through the issuance of a letter of authorization.

CAAF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Contractor employees and all tiers of subcontractor employees who are authorized to accompany the force in applicable contingency operations outside of the United States and have afforded such status through the issuance of a letter of authorization.

control_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Authority that may be less than full command exercised by a commander over part of the activities of subordinate or other organizations. (JP 1) 2. In mapping, charting, and photogrammetry, a collective term for a system of marks or objects on the Earth or on a map or a photograph, whose positions or elevations (or both) have been or will be determined. (JP 2-03) 3. Physical or psychological pressures exerted with the intent to assure that an agent or group will respond as directed. (JP 3-0) 4. In intelligence usage, an indicator governing the distribution and use of documents, information, or material.

control group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Personnel and ships designated to control the surface ship-to-shore movement.

controlled substance_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A drug or other substance, or immediate precursor, included in Schedule I, II, III, IV, or V of the Controlled Substances Act.

control point_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A position along a route of march at which personnel are stationed to give information and instructions for the regulation of supply or traffic. 2. A position marked by coordinates (latitude, longitude), a buoy, boat, aircraft, electronic device, conspicuous terrain feature, or other identifiable object, which is given a name or number and used as an aid to navigation or control of ships, boats, or aircraft. 3. In marking mosaics, a point located by ground survey with which a corresponding point on a photograph is matched as a check.

conventional forces_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: 1. Those forces capable of conducting operations using nonnuclear weapons. 2. Those forces other than designated special operations forces.

CF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Those forces capable of conducting operations using nonnuclear weapons. 2. Those forces other than designated special operations forces.

convoy escort_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A naval ship(s) or aircraft in company with a convoy and responsible for its protection. 2. An escort to protect a convoy of vehicles from being scattered, destroyed, or captured.

coordinated fire line_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A line beyond which conventional surface-to-surface direct fire and indirect fire support means may fire at any time within the boundaries of the establishing headquarters without additional coordination but does not eliminate the responsibility to coordinate the airspace required to conduct the mission.

CFL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A line beyond which conventional surface-to-surface direct fire and indirect fire support means may fire at any time within the boundaries of the establishing headquarters without additional coordination but does not eliminate the responsibility to coordinate the airspace required to conduct the mission.

coordinating altitude_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: An airspace coordinating measure that uses altitude to separate users and as the transition between different airspace control elements.

coordinating review authority_|_dod_dict.paragraph: In joint doctrine development and maintenance, an agency appointed by the Joint Staff, a Service, a combatant command, or a combat support agency to coordinate with and assist the lead agent, primary review authority, Joint Staff doctrine sponsor, and assessment agent.

CRA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In joint doctrine development and maintenance, an agency appointed by the Joint Staff, a Service, a combatant command, or a combat support agency to coordinate with and assist the lead agent, primary review authority, Joint Staff doctrine sponsor, and assessment agent.

cost-type contract_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A contract that provides for payment to the contractor of allowable costs, to the extent prescribed in the contract, incurred in performance of the contract.

counterdeception_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Efforts to negate, neutralize, diminish the effects of, or gain advantage from a foreign deception operation.

counterdrug activities_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Those measures taken to detect, interdict, disrupt, or curtail any activity that is reasonably related to illicit drug trafficking.

counterdrug operations_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Civil or military actions taken to reduce or eliminate illicit drug trafficking.

counterfire_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire intended to destroy or neutralize enemy weapons.

countering threat networks_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The aggregation of activities across the Department of Defense and United States Government departments and agencies that identifies and neutralizes, degrades, disrupts, or defeats designated threat networks.

CTN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The aggregation of activities across the Department of Defense and United States Government departments and agencies that identifies and neutralizes, degrades, disrupts, or defeats designated threat networks.

counterinsurgency_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Comprehensive civilian and military efforts designed to simultaneously defeat and contain insurgency and address its root causes.

COIN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Comprehensive civilian and military efforts designed to simultaneously defeat and contain insurgency and address its root causes.

counterintelligence activities_|_dod_dic.paragraph: One or more of the five functions of counterintelligence: operations, investigations, collection, analysis and production, and functional services. See also analysis and production; collection; counterintelligence; operation.

counterintelligence operational tasking.paragraph: The levying of counterintelligence requirements specific to military activities and operations.

CIOTA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The levying of counterintelligence requirements specific to military activities and operations.

counterintelligence production_|_dod_dic.paragraph: The creation of finished intelligence products incorporating counterintelligence analysis in response to known or anticipated customer counterintelligence concerns.

countermeasures_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That form of military science that, by the employment of devices and/or techniques, has as its objective the impairment of the operational effectiveness of enemy activity.

counterproliferation_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: Those actions taken to reduce the risks posed by extant weapons of mass destruction to the United States, allies, and partners.

counter threat finance_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Activities conducted to deny, disrupt, destroy, or defeat the generation, storage, movement, and use of assets to fund activities that support an adversary's ability to negatively affect United States interests.

CTF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Activities conducted to deny, disrupt, destroy, or defeat the generation, storage, movement, and use of assets to fund activities that support an adversary's ability to negatively affect United States interests.

courier_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A messenger (usually a commissioned or warrant officer) responsible for the secure physical transmission and delivery of documents and material.
