landing diagram_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A graphic means of illustrating the plan for the ship-to-shore movement.

landing force operational reserve materi.paragraph: Package of contingency supplies pre-positioned and maintained onboard selected amphibious warfare ships to enhance reaction time and provide support for the embarked landing force in contingencies.

LFORM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Package of contingency supplies pre-positioned and maintained onboard selected amphibious warfare ships to enhance reaction time and provide support for the embarked landing force in contingencies.

landing group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, a subordinate task organization of the landing force capable of conducting landing operations, under a single tactical command, against a position or group of positions.

landing sequence table_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A document that incorporates the detailed plans for ship-to-shore movement of nonscheduled units.

landing zone_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any specified zone used for the landing of aircraft.

LZ_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any specified zone used for the landing of aircraft.

laser rangefinder_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A device that uses laser energy for determining the distance from the device to a place or object.

laser spot_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The area on a surface illuminated by a laser.

laser target designator_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A device that emits a beam of laser energy that is used to mark a specific place or object.

LTD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A device that emits a beam of laser energy that is used to mark a specific place or object.

launch area denied_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The geographic area from which an enemy targeting a designated defended area cannot launch a ballistic missile without it being engaged by the ballistic missile defenses.

LAD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The geographic area from which an enemy targeting a designated defended area cannot launch a ballistic missile without it being engaged by the ballistic missile defenses.

law enforcement agency_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Any of a number of agencies (outside the Department of Defense) chartered and empowered to enforce United States laws in a state or territory (or political subdivision) of the United States, a federally recognized Native American tribe or Alaskan Native Village, or within the borders of a host nation.

LEA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any of a number of agencies (outside the Department of Defense) chartered and empowered to enforce United States laws in a state or territory (or political subdivision) of the United States, a federally recognized Native American tribe or Alaskan Native Village, or within the borders of a host nation.

law of war_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That part of international law that regulates the conduct of armed hostilities.

the law of armed conflict_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: That part of international law that regulates the conduct of armed hostilities.

lead agency_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The United States Government agency designated to coordinate the interagency oversight of the day-to-day conduct of an ongoing operation.

lead aircraft_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The airborne aircraft designated to exercise command of other aircraft within the flight.

lead nation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The nation with the will, capability, competence, and influence to provide the essential elements of political consultation and military leadership to coordinate the planning, mounting, and execution of a multinational operation.

LN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The nation with the will, capability, competence, and influence to provide the essential elements of political consultation and military leadership to coordinate the planning, mounting, and execution of a multinational operation.

letter of assist_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A contractual document issued by the United Nations to a government authorizing it to provide goods or services to a peacekeeping operation.

LOA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A contractual document issued by the United Nations to a government authorizing it to provide goods or services to a peacekeeping operation.

LOA_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: That geographic area required to conduct a logistics over-the-shore operation.

level of detail_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Within the current joint planning and execution system, movement characteristics for both personnel and cargo are described at six distinct levels of detail. Levels I, V, and VI describe personnel and Levels I through IV and VI for cargo. Levels I through IV are coded and visible in the Joint Operation Planning and Execution System automated data processing. Levels V and VI are used by Joint Operation Planning and Execution System automated data processing feeder systems. a. level I - personnel: expressed as total number of passengers by unit line number. Cargo: expressed in total short tons, total measurement tons, total square feet, and total thousands of barrels by unit line number. Petroleum, oils, and lubricants is expressed by thousands of barrels by unit line number. b. level II - cargo: expressed by short tons and measurement tons of bulk, oversize, outsize, and non-air transportable cargo by unit line number. Also square feet for vehicles and non self-deployable aircraft and boats by unit line number. c. level III - cargo: detail by cargo category code expressed as short tons and measurement tons as well as square feet associated to that cargo category code for an individual unit line number. d. level IV - cargo: detail for individual dimensional data expressed in length, width, and height in number of inches, and weight/volume in short tons/measurement tons, along with a cargo description. Each cargo item is associated with a cargo category code and a unit line number). e. level V - personnel: any general summarization/aggregation of level VI detail in distribution and deployment. f. level VI - personnel: detail expressed by name, Service, military occupational specialty and unique identification number. Cargo: detail expressed by association to a transportation control number or single tracking number or item of equipment to include federal stock number/national stock number and/or requisition number. Nested cargo, cargo that is contained within another equipment item, may similarly be identified.

L-hour_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The specific hour on C-day at which a deployment operation commences or is to commence. (JP 5-0) 2. In amphibious operations, the time at which the first helicopter or tiltrotor aircraft of the airborne ship-to-shore movement wave touches down or is scheduled to touch down in a landing zone.

lighterage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process in which small craft are used to transport cargo or personnel from ship-to-shore using amphibians, landing craft, discharge lighters, causeways, and barges.

limiting factor_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A factor or condition that, either temporarily or permanently, impedes mission accomplishment.

line of demarcation_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A line defining the boundary of a buffer zone used to establish the forward limits of disputing or belligerent forces after each phase of disengagement or withdrawal has been completed.

line of effort_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In the context of planning, using the purpose (cause and effect) to focus efforts toward establishing operational and strategic conditions by linking multiple tasks and missions.

LOE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In the context of planning, using the purpose (cause and effect) to focus efforts toward establishing operational and strategic conditions by linking multiple tasks and missions.

link_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A behavioral, physical, or functional relationship between nodes. 2. In communications, a general term used to indicate the existence of communications facilities between two points. 3. A maritime route, other than a coastal or transit route, that connects any two or more routes together.

littoral_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The littoral comprises two segments of operational environment: 1. Seaward: the area from the open ocean to the shore, which must be controlled to support operations ashore. 2. Landward: the area inland from the shore that can be supported and defended directly from the sea.

load signal_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In personnel recovery, a visual signal displayed in a covert manner to indicate the presence of an individual or object at a given location.

lodgment_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A designated area in a hostile or potentially hostile operational area that, when seized and held, makes the continuous landing of troops and materiel possible and provides maneuver space for subsequent operations.

logistics over-the-shore operation area_.paragraph: That geographic area required to conduct a logistics over-the-shore operation.

logistics supportability analysis_|_dod_.paragraph: Combatant command internal assessment for the Joint Strategic Campaign Plan on capabilities and shortfalls of key logistic capabilities required to execute and sustain the concept of support conducted on all level three and four plans with the time phased force deployment data.

LSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Combatant command internal assessment for the Joint Strategic Campaign Plan on capabilities and shortfalls of key logistic capabilities required to execute and sustain the concept of support conducted on all level three and four plans with the time phased force deployment data.

low-level transit route_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A temporary corridor of defined dimensions established in the forward area to minimize the risk to friendly aircraft from friendly air defenses or surface forces.

LLTR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A temporary corridor of defined dimensions established in the forward area to minimize the risk to friendly aircraft from friendly air defenses or surface forces.

low-visibility operations_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Sensitive actions or activities wherein the diplomatic-military restrictions inherent in covert and clandestine operations are either not necessary or not feasible. (JP 3-05) M

mail embargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A temporary shutdown or redirection of mail flow to or from a specific location.

main supply route_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The route or routes designated within an operational area upon which the bulk of traffic flows in support of military operations. Also called MSR.

major force_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A military organization comprised of major combat elements and associated combat support, combat service support, and sustainment increments.

maneuver_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A movement to place ships, aircraft, or land forces in a position of advantage over the enemy. 2. A tactical exercise carried out at sea, in the air, on the ground, or on a map in imitation of war. 3. The operation of a ship, aircraft, or vehicle to cause it to perform desired movements. 4. Employment of forces in the operational area, through movement in combination with fires and information, to achieve a position of advantage in respect to the enemy.

manpower requirements_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Human resources needed to accomplish specified workloads of organizations.

Marine special operations forces_|_dod_d.paragraph: Those Active Component Marine Corps forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

MARSOF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Those Active Component Marine Corps forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

Maritime Administration Ready Reserve Fo.paragraph: The surge sealift assets owned and operated by the United States Department of Transportation/Maritime Administration and Military Sealift Command (in contingency), crewed by civilian mariners.

MARAD RRF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The surge sealift assets owned and operated by the United States Department of Transportation/Maritime Administration and Military Sealift Command (in contingency), crewed by civilian mariners.

maritime domain awareness_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: The effective understanding of anything associated with the maritime domain that could impact the security, safety, economy, or environment of a nation.

MDA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The effective understanding of anything associated with the maritime domain that could impact the security, safety, economy, or environment of a nation.

maritime forces_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Forces that operate on, under, or above the sea to gain or exploit command of the sea, sea control, or sea denial and/or to project power from the sea.

maritime power projection_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Power projection in and from the maritime environment, including a broad spectrum of offensive military operations to destroy enemy forces or logistic support or to prevent enemy forces from approaching within enemy weapons' range of friendly forces.

maritime pre-positioning ships_|_dod_dic.paragraph: Civilian-crewed, Military Sealift Command-chartered ships that are usually forward-deployed and loaded with pre-positioned equipment and up to 30 days of supplies to support Marine expeditionary brigades.

MPSs_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Civilian-crewed, Military Sealift Command-chartered ships that are usually forward-deployed and loaded with pre-positioned equipment and up to 30 days of supplies to support Marine expeditionary brigades.

Maritime Security Program_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A program authorized in the Maritime Security Act of 2003 requiring the Secretary of Transportation, in consultation with the Secretary of Defense, to establish a fleet of active, commercially viable, militarily useful, privately-owned vessels to meet national defense and other security requirements.

MSP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A program authorized in the Maritime Security Act of 2003 requiring the Secretary of Transportation, in consultation with the Secretary of Defense, to establish a fleet of active, commercially viable, militarily useful, privately-owned vessels to meet national defense and other security requirements.

maritime supremacy_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: That degree of maritime superiority wherein an opposing force is incapable of effective interference.

marking_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: To maintain contact on a target from such a position that the marking unit has an immediate offensive capability.

marshalling area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A location in the vicinity of a reception terminal or pre-positioned equipment storage site where arriving unit personnel, equipment, materiel, and accompanying supplies are reassembled, returned to the control of the unit commander, and prepared for onward movement.

mass casualty_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any number of human casualties produced across a period of time that exceeds available medical support capabilities.

master_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The commander of a United States Naval Ship, a commercial ship, or a government-owned general agency agreement ship operated for the Military Sealift Command by a civilian company to transport Department of Defense cargo.

materials handling equipment_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: Equipment used at air, ground, and sea ports to handle large cargo.

MHE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Equipment used at air, ground, and sea ports to handle large cargo.

materiel inventory objective_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: The quantity of an item required to be on hand and on order on M-day to equip, provide a materiel pipeline, and sustain the approved United States force structure and those Allied forces designated for United States materiel support, through the period prescribed for war materiel planning purposes.

materiel release order_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An order issued by an accountable supply system manager directing a nonaccountable activity within the same supply distribution complex to release and ship materiel.

MRO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An order issued by an accountable supply system manager directing a nonaccountable activity within the same supply distribution complex to release and ship materiel.

maximum ordinate_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In artillery and naval gunfire support, the height of the highest point in the trajectory of a projectile above the horizontal plane passing through its origin.

vertex height and MAXORD_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: In artillery and naval gunfire support, the height of the highest point in the trajectory of a projectile above the horizontal plane passing through its origin.

Measurement and Signature Intelligence R.paragraph: A system for the management of theater and national measurement and signature intelligence collection requirements, providing automated tools for users in support of submission, review, and validation of measurement and signature intelligence nominations of requirements to be tasked for national and Department of Defense measurement and signature intelligence collection, production, and exploitation resources. Also called MRS. See also measurement and signature intelligence.

measure of effectiveness_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: An indicator used to measure a current system state, with change indicated by comparing multiple observations over time.

MOE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An indicator used to measure a current system state, with change indicated by comparing multiple observations over time.

mechanical sweep_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In naval mine warfare, any sweep used with the object of physically contacting the mine or its appendages.

media pool_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A limited number of news media who represent a larger number of news media organizations for purposes of news gathering and sharing of material during a specified activity.

medical intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: That category of intelligence resulting from collection, evaluation, analysis, and interpretation of foreign medical, bio-scientific, and environmental information that is of interest to strategic planning and to military medical planning and operations for the conservation of the fighting strength of friendly forces and the formation of assessments of foreign medical capabilities in both military and civilian sectors.

MEDINT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That category of intelligence resulting from collection, evaluation, analysis, and interpretation of foreign medical, bio-scientific, and environmental information that is of interest to strategic planning and to military medical planning and operations for the conservation of the fighting strength of friendly forces and the formation of assessments of foreign medical capabilities in both military and civilian sectors.

medical logistics support_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Class VIII medical supplies (medical material to include medical peculiar repair parts used to sustain the health service support system), optical fabrication, medical equipment maintenance, blood storage and distribution, and medical gases.

MEDLOG support_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Class VIII medical supplies (medical material to include medical peculiar repair parts used to sustain the health service support system), optical fabrication, medical equipment maintenance, blood storage and distribution, and medical gases.

medical surveillance_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The ongoing, systematic collection, analysis, and interpretation of data derived from instances of medical care or medical evaluation, and the reporting of population-based information for characterizing and countering threats to a population's health, well-being, and performance.

medical treatment protocol_|_dod_diction.paragraph: Directive issued by competent military authority that delineate the circumstances and limitations under which United States medical forces will initiate medical care and support to those individuals that are not Department of Defense health care beneficiaries or designated eligible for care in a military medical treatment facility by the Secretary of Defense.

mensuration_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of measurement of a feature or location on the Earth to determine an absolute latitude, longitude, and elevation.

meteorological and oceanographic_|_dod_d.paragraph: A term used to convey all environmental factors, from the sub-bottom of the Earth's oceans through maritime, land areas, airspace, ionosphere, and outward into space.

METOC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A term used to convey all environmental factors, from the sub-bottom of the Earth's oceans through maritime, land areas, airspace, ionosphere, and outward into space.

meteorological and oceanographic data_|_.paragraph: Measurements or observations of meteorological and oceanographic variables.

meteorology_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The study dealing with the phenomena of the atmosphere including the physics, chemistry, and dynamics extending to the effects of the atmosphere on the Earth's surface and the oceans.

migrant_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A person who belongs to a normally migratory culture who may cross national boundaries or has fled their native country for economic reasons rather than fear of political or ethnic persecution.

military construction_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Any construction, alteration, development, conversion, or extension of any kind carried out with respect to a military installation.

MILCON_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any construction, alteration, development, conversion, or extension of any kind carried out with respect to a military installation.

Military Department_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: One of the departments within the Department of Defense created by the National Security Act of 1947, which are the Department of the Army, the Department of the Navy, and the Department of the Air Force.

MILDEP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: One of the departments within the Department of Defense created by the National Security Act of 1947, which are the Department of the Army, the Department of the Navy, and the Department of the Air Force.

military government_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The supreme authority the military exercises by force or agreement over the lands, property, and indigenous populations and institutions of domestic, allied, neutral, or enemy territory, therefore, substituting sovereign authority under rule of law for the previously established government.

military information support operations_.paragraph: Planned operations to convey selected information and indicators to foreign audiences to influence their emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behavior of foreign governments, organizations, groups, and individuals in a manner favorable to the originator's objectives.

MISO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Planned operations to convey selected information and indicators to foreign audiences to influence their emotions, motives, objective reasoning, and ultimately the behavior of foreign governments, organizations, groups, and individuals in a manner favorable to the originator's objectives.

military intervention_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The deliberate act of a nation or a group of nations to introduce its military forces into the course of an existing controversy.

Military Postal Service_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The command, organization, personnel, and facilities established to provide a means for the delivery of mail to and from the Department of Defense, members of the Armed Forces of the United States, and other authorized agencies and individuals.

MPS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The command, organization, personnel, and facilities established to provide a means for the delivery of mail to and from the Department of Defense, members of the Armed Forces of the United States, and other authorized agencies and individuals.

Military Sealift Command_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: A major command of the United States Navy reporting to Commander Fleet Forces Command, and the United States Transportation Command's component command responsible for designated common-user sealift transportation services to deploy, employ, sustain, and redeploy United States forces on a global basis.

MSC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A major command of the United States Navy reporting to Commander Fleet Forces Command, and the United States Transportation Command's component command responsible for designated common-user sealift transportation services to deploy, employ, sustain, and redeploy United States forces on a global basis.

military source operations_|_dod_diction.paragraph: The collection, from, by and/or via humans, of foreign and military and military-related intelligence.

military standard transportation and mov.query: military standard transportation and movement procedures
military standard transportation and mov.paragraph: Uniform and standard transportation data, documentation, and control procedures applicable to all cargo movements in the Department of Defense transportation system. Also called MILSTAMP.

mine_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1.In land mine warfare, a munition placed under, on or near the ground or other surface area and designed to be exploded by the presence, proximity or contact of a person or vehicle. 2. In naval mine warfare, an explosive device laid in the water with the intention of damaging or sinking ships or of deterring shipping from entering an area.

minefield_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In land warfare, an area of ground containing mines emplaced with or without a pattern. 2. In naval warfare, an area of water containing mines emplaced with or without a pattern.

minefield report_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An oral, electronic, or written communication concerning mining activities (friendly or enemy) submitted in a standard format by the fastest secure means available.

minesweeping_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The technique of clearing mines using either mechanical sweeping to remove, disturb, or otherwise neutralize the mine; explosive sweeping to cause sympathetic detonations, damage, or displace the mine; or influence sweeping to produce either the acoustic or magnetic influence required to detonate the mine.

minimize_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A condition wherein normal message and telephone traffic is drastically reduced so messages connected with an actual or simulated emergency shall not be delayed.

minimum-risk route_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A temporary corridor of defined dimensions recommended for use by high-speed, fixed-wing aircraft that presents the minimum known hazards to low-flying aircraft transiting the combat zone.

MRR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A temporary corridor of defined dimensions recommended for use by high-speed, fixed-wing aircraft that presents the minimum known hazards to low-flying aircraft transiting the combat zone.

missile engagement zone_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: In air and missile defense, that airspace of defined dimensions within which the responsibility for engagement of air and missile threats normally rests with surface-to-air missile systems.

MEZ_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In air and missile defense, that airspace of defined dimensions within which the responsibility for engagement of air and missile threats normally rests with surface-to-air missile systems.

mission assignment_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The vehicle used by the Department of Homeland Security/Emergency Preparedness and Response/Federal Emergency Management Agency to support federal operations in a declared Stafford Act major disaster or emergency declaration that orders immediate, short-term emergency response assistance when an applicable state or local government is overwhelmed by the event and lacks the capability to perform, or contract for, the necessary work.

mission command_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The conduct of military operations through decentralized execution based upon mission-type orders.

mission-oriented protective posture gear.paragraph: Military term for individual protective equipment, including suit, boots, gloves, mask with hood, first aid treatments, and decontamination kits, issued to authorized personnel.

MOPP gear_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Military term for individual protective equipment, including suit, boots, gloves, mask with hood, first aid treatments, and decontamination kits, issued to authorized personnel.

mission type order_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: 1. An order issued to a lower unit that includes the accomplishment of the total mission assigned to the higher headquarters. 2. An order to a unit to perform a mission without specifying how it is to be accomplished.

mobility_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A quality or capability of military forces which permits them to move from place to place while retaining the ability to fulfill their primary mission.

mobility corridor_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Areas that are relatively free of obstacles where a force will be canalized due to terrain restrictions allowing military forces to capitalize on the principles of mass and speed.

mobilization base_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The total of all resources available, or that can be made available, to meet foreseeable wartime needs.

mobilization station_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The designated military installation to which a Reserve Component unit or individual is moved for further processing, organizing, equipping, training, and employment and from which the unit or individual may move to an aerial port of embarkation or seaport of embarkation.

Modernized Integrated Database_|_dod_dic.paragraph: The national-level repository for the general military intelligence available to the entire Department of Defense Intelligence Information System community and, through Global Command and Control System integrated imagery and intelligence, to tactical units.

MIDB_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The national-level repository for the general military intelligence available to the entire Department of Defense Intelligence Information System community and, through Global Command and Control System integrated imagery and intelligence, to tactical units.

moored mine_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A contact or influence-operated mine of positive buoyancy held below the surface by a mooring attached to a sinker or anchor on the bottom.

mortuary affairs_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Provides for the search, recovery, identification, preparation, and disposition of human remains of persons for whom the Services are responsible by status and executive order.

MA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Provides for the search, recovery, identification, preparation, and disposition of human remains of persons for whom the Services are responsible by status and executive order.

movement control_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The planning, routing, scheduling, and control of personnel and cargo movements over lines of communications; includes maintaining in-transit visibility of forces and material through the deployment and/or redeployment process.

movement data_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Those essential elements of information to schedule lift, obtain transportation assets, manage movement of forces, and report in-transit visibility of movements and associated forces (people, equipment, and supplies).

movement phase_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the period during which various elements of the amphibious force move from points of embarkation or forward-deployed locations to the objective area.

movement requirement_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A stated movement mode and time-phased need for the transport of units, personnel, and/or materiel from a specified origin to a specified destination.

movement table_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A table giving detailed instructions or data for a move.

multinational_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Between two or more forces or agencies of two or more nations or coalition partners.

multinational force_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A force composed of military elements of nations who have formed an alliance or coalition for some specific purpose.

MNF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A force composed of military elements of nations who have formed an alliance or coalition for some specific purpose.

multinational integrated logistic unit_|.paragraph: An organization resulting when two or more nations agree to provide logistics assets to a multinational logistic force under the operational control of a multinational commander for the logistic support of a multinational force.

MILU_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organization resulting when two or more nations agree to provide logistics assets to a multinational logistic force under the operational control of a multinational commander for the logistic support of a multinational force.

multinational operations_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: A collective term to describe military actions conducted by forces of two or more nations, usually undertaken within the structure of a coalition or alliance.

multipoint refueling system_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: KC-135 aircraft equipped with external wing-mounted pods to conduct drogue air refueling, while still maintaining boom air refueling capability on the same mission.

munitions effectiveness assessment_|_dod.paragraph: The assessment of the military force applied in terms of the weapon system and munitions effectiveness to determine and recommend any required changes to the methodology, tactics, weapon system, munitions, fusing, and/or weapon delivery parameters to increase force effectiveness.

MEA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The assessment of the military force applied in terms of the weapon system and munitions effectiveness to determine and recommend any required changes to the methodology, tactics, weapon system, munitions, fusing, and/or weapon delivery parameters to increase force effectiveness.

named area of interest_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: The geospatial area or systems node or link against which information that will satisfy a specific information requirement can be collected, usually to capture indications of adversary courses of action.

NAI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The geospatial area or systems node or link against which information that will satisfy a specific information requirement can be collected, usually to capture indications of adversary courses of action.

National Capital Region_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A geographic area encompassing the District of Columbia and 11 local jurisdictions in the State of Maryland and the Commonwealth of Virginia.

NCR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A geographic area encompassing the District of Columbia and 11 local jurisdictions in the State of Maryland and the Commonwealth of Virginia.

National Detainee Reporting Center_|_dod.paragraph: The national-level center that accounts for all persons who pass through the care, custody, and control of the Department of Defense and that obtains and stores information concerning detainees and their confiscated personal property.

NDRC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The national-level center that accounts for all persons who pass through the care, custody, and control of the Department of Defense and that obtains and stores information concerning detainees and their confiscated personal property.

national emergency_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A condition declared by the President or Congress by virtue of powers previously vested in them that authorize certain emergency actions to be undertaken in the national interest.

national intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: All intelligence that pertains to more than one agency and involves threats to the United States, its people, property, or interests; the development, proliferation, or use of weapons of mass destruction; or any other matter bearing on United States national or homeland security.

national military strategy_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A document approved by the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff for distributing and applying military power to attain national security strategy and Defense Strategic Guidance objectives.

NMS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A document approved by the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff for distributing and applying military power to attain national security strategy and Defense Strategic Guidance objectives.

national preparedness_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Actions taken to plan, organize, equip, train, and exercise to build and sustain the capabilities necessary to prevent, protect against, mitigate the effects of, respond to, and recover from those threats that pose the greatest risk to the security of the nation.

National Security Council_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A governmental body specifically designed to assist the President in integrating all spheres of national security policy.

NSC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A governmental body specifically designed to assist the President in integrating all spheres of national security policy.

national security space_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The space-related systems, services, capabilities, and associated information networks of the Department of Defense and the national intelligence community, or other space-related systems that the Secretary of Defense may designate as national security space systems in coordination with the system owner, that support United States national security and enable defense and intelligence operations during times of peace, crisis, or conflict.

national shipping authority_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: The organization within each Allied government responsible in time of war for the direction of its own merchant shipping.

NSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The organization within each Allied government responsible in time of war for the direction of its own merchant shipping.

national stock number_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The 13-digit number that identifies a stock item consisting of the 4-digit federal supply classification code plus the 9-digit national item identification number and arranged as follows: 9999-00-999-9999.

NSN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The 13-digit number that identifies a stock item consisting of the 4-digit federal supply classification code plus the 9-digit national item identification number and arranged as follows: 9999-00-999-9999.

National System for Geospatial Intellige.paragraph: The combination of technology, policies, capabilities, doctrine, activities, people, data, and organizations necessary to produce geospatial intelligence in an integrated, multi-intelligence environment.

NSG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The combination of technology, policies, capabilities, doctrine, activities, people, data, and organizations necessary to produce geospatial intelligence in an integrated, multi-intelligence environment.

naval advanced logistic support site_|_d.paragraph: An overseas location used as the primary transshipment point in the theater of operations for logistic support.

NALSS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An overseas location used as the primary transshipment point in the theater of operations for logistic support.

naval construction force_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The combined construction units of the Navy that are part of the operating forces and represent the Navy's capability for advanced base construction.

NCF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The combined construction units of the Navy that are part of the operating forces and represent the Navy's capability for advanced base construction.

naval gunfire support_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Fire provided by Navy surface gun systems in support of a unit or units tasked with achieving the commander's objectives.

NGFS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire provided by Navy surface gun systems in support of a unit or units tasked with achieving the commander's objectives.

naval special warfare_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A naval warfare specialty that conducts special operations with an emphasis on maritime, coastal, and riverine environments using small, flexible, mobile units operating under, on, and from the sea.

NSW_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A naval warfare specialty that conducts special operations with an emphasis on maritime, coastal, and riverine environments using small, flexible, mobile units operating under, on, and from the sea.

naval special warfare task group_|_dod_d.paragraph: A provisional naval special warfare organization that plans, conducts, and supports special operations in support of fleet commanders and joint force special operations component commanders. Also called NSWTG.

naval surface fire support_|_dod_diction.paragraph: Fire provided by Navy surface gun and missile systems in support of a unit or units.

NSFS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire provided by Navy surface gun and missile systems in support of a unit or units.

Navy cargo-handling battalion_|_dod_dict.paragraph: A mobile logistic support unit that is organized, trained, and equipped to: a. load and off-load Navy and Marine Corps cargo carried in maritime pre-positioning ships and merchant breakbulk or container ships in all environments, b. operate an associated temporary ocean cargo terminal, c. load and off-load Navy and Marine Corps cargo carried in military-controlled aircraft, and d. operate an associated expeditionary air cargo terminal. Also called NCHB. See also maritime pre-positioning ships.

Navy special operations forces_|_dod_dic.paragraph: Those Active Component and Reserve Component Navy forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

NAVSOF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Those Active Component and Reserve Component Navy forces designated by the Secretary of Defense that are specifically organized, trained, and equipped to conduct and support special operations.

Navy tactical air control center_|_dod_d.paragraph: The principal air operations installation (ship-based) from which all aircraft and air warning functions of tactical air operations are controlled.

Navy TACC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The principal air operations installation (ship-based) from which all aircraft and air warning functions of tactical air operations are controlled.

need to know_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A criterion used in security procedures that requires the custodians of classified information to establish, prior to disclosure, that the intended recipient must have access to the information to perform his or her official duties.

nerve agent_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A potentially lethal chemical agent that interferes with the transmission of nerve impulses.

networked munitions_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Remotely controlled, interconnected, weapons systems designed to provide rapidly emplaced ground-based countermobility and protection capability through scalable application of lethal and nonlethal means.

neutral_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In combat and combat support operations, an identity applied to a track whose characteristics, behavior, origin, or nationality indicate that it is neither supporting nor opposing friendly forces.

neutralize_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. As pertains to military operations, to render ineffective or unusable. 2. To render enemy personnel or materiel incapable of interfering with a particular operation. 3. To render safe mines, bombs, missiles, and booby traps. 4. To make harmless anything contaminated with a chemical agent.

night-vision goggle_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: An electro-optical, image-intensifying device that detects visible and near-infrared energy, intensifies the energy, and provides a visible image for night viewing.

NVG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An electro-optical, image-intensifying device that detects visible and near-infrared energy, intensifies the energy, and provides a visible image for night viewing.

no-fire area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An area designated by the appropriate commander into which fires or their effects are prohibited.

NFA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An area designated by the appropriate commander into which fires or their effects are prohibited.

nonbattle injury_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A person who becomes a casualty due to circumstances not directly attributable to hostile action or terrorist activity.

NBI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A person who becomes a casualty due to circumstances not directly attributable to hostile action or terrorist activity.

noncombatant evacuation operation tracki.paragraph: An automated data processing hardware and software package that has the capability to provide evacuee in-transit visibility to combatant commanders and senior leadership during the conduct of a noncombatant evacuation operation.

NTS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An automated data processing hardware and software package that has the capability to provide evacuee in-transit visibility to combatant commanders and senior leadership during the conduct of a noncombatant evacuation operation.

nonconventional assisted recovery_|_dod_.paragraph: Personnel recovery conducted by indigenous/surrogate personnel that are trained, supported, and led by special operations forces, unconventional warfare ground and maritime forces, or other government agencies' personnel that have been specifically trained and directed to establish and operate indigenous or surrogate infrastructures.

NAR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Personnel recovery conducted by indigenous/surrogate personnel that are trained, supported, and led by special operations forces, unconventional warfare ground and maritime forces, or other government agencies' personnel that have been specifically trained and directed to establish and operate indigenous or surrogate infrastructures.

nonlethal reference point_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A point that designates the intended target for creating nonlethal effects, which may not be a precise physical location and is considered an aimpoint for databasing.

NLRP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A point that designates the intended target for creating nonlethal effects, which may not be a precise physical location and is considered an aimpoint for databasing.

nonpersistent agent_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A chemical agent that, when released, dissipates and/or loses its ability to cause casualties after 10 to 15 minutes.

nonproliferation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Actions to prevent the acquisition of weapons of mass destruction by dissuading or impeding access to, or distribution of, sensitive technologies, material, and expertise.

non-unit cargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All equipment and supplies requiring transportation to an operational area, other than those identified as the equipment or accompanying supplies of a specific unit. (JP 4-01.5).

no-strike list_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A list of objects or entities characterized as protected from the effects of military operations under international law and/or rules of engagement.

NSL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A list of objects or entities characterized as protected from the effects of military operations under international law and/or rules of engagement.

nuclear hazard_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Dangers associated with the blast, thermal, and radiation effects from nuclear explosion.

nuisance minefield_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A minefield laid to delay and disorganize the enemy and to hinder the use of an area or route.

numbered fleet_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A major tactical unit of the Navy immediately subordinate to a major fleet command and comprising various task forces, elements, groups, and units for the purpose of prosecuting specific naval operations.

objective_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The clearly defined, decisive, and attainable goal toward which an operation is directed. 2. The specific goal of the action taken which is essential to the commander's plan.

observable_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In military deception, the detectable result of the combination of an indicator within an adversary's conduit intended to cause action or inaction by the deception target.

obstacle belt_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A brigade-level command and control measure, normally depicted graphically, to show where within an obstacle zone the ground tactical commander plans to limit friendly obstacle employment and focus the defense.

obstacle restricted areas_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A command and control measure used to limit the type or number of obstacles within an area.

oceanography_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The study of the sea, embracing and integrating all knowledge pertaining to the sea and its physical boundaries, the chemistry and physics of seawater, and marine biology.

offensive counterair attack operations_|.paragraph: Offensive action by any part of the joint force in support of the offensive counterair mission against surface targets which contribute to the enemy's air and missile capabilities.

OCA attack operations_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Offensive action by any part of the joint force in support of the offensive counterair mission against surface targets which contribute to the enemy's air and missile capabilities.

offensive cyberspace operations_|_dod_di.paragraph: Missions intended to project power in and through cyberspace.

OCO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Missions intended to project power in and through cyberspace.

office_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An enduring organization that is formed around a specific function within a headquarters to coordinate and manage support requirements.

official information_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: Information that is owned by, produced for or by, or is subject to the control of the United States Government.

offshore bulk fuel system_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: The system used for transferring fuel from points offshore to reception facilities on the beach.

OBFS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The system used for transferring fuel from points offshore to reception facilities on the beach.

on-call_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A term used to signify that a prearranged concentration, air strike, or final protective fire may be called for. 2. Preplanned, identified force or materiel requirements without designated time-phase and destination information.

on hand_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The quantity of an item that is physically available in a storage location and contained in the accountable property book records of an issuing activity.

on-station time_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The time an aircraft can remain on station, which may be determined by endurance or orders.

open-source information_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: Information that any member of the public could lawfully obtain by request or observation as well as other unclassified information that has limited public distribution or access.

operating stocks_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fuel required to sustain daily operations and ensure fuel availability to support United States military forces worldwide.

OS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fuel required to sustain daily operations and ensure fuel availability to support United States military forces worldwide.

operational access_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The ability to project military force into an operational area with sufficient freedom of action to accomplish the mission.

operational area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An overarching term encompassing more descriptive terms (such as area of responsibility and joint operations area) for geographic areas in which military operations are conducted.

OA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An overarching term encompassing more descriptive terms (such as area of responsibility and joint operations area) for geographic areas in which military operations are conducted.

operational characteristics_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: Those military characteristics that pertain primarily to the functions to be performed by equipment, either alone or in conjunction with other equipment; e.g., for electronic equipment, operational characteristics include such items as frequency coverage, channeling, type of modulation, and character of emission.

operational contract support integration.paragraph: A cell established to coordinate and integrate operational contract support actions across all primary and special staffs for an operational area.

OCSIC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A cell established to coordinate and integrate operational contract support actions across all primary and special staffs for an operational area.

operational control authority_|_dod_dict.paragraph: The naval commander responsible within a specified geographical area for the naval control of all merchant shipping under Allied naval control.

OCA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The naval commander responsible within a specified geographical area for the naval control of all merchant shipping under Allied naval control.

operational decontamination_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: Decontamination carried out by an individual and/or a unit, restricted to specific parts of operationally essential equipment, materiel, and/or working areas, to minimize contact and transfer hazards and to sustain operations.

operational energy_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The energy required for training, moving, and sustaining military forces and weapons platforms for military operations.

operational exposure guidance_|_dod_dict.paragraph: The maximum amount of nuclear/external ionizing radiation that the commander considers a unit may be permitted to receive while performing a particular mission or missions.

OEG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The maximum amount of nuclear/external ionizing radiation that the commander considers a unit may be permitted to receive while performing a particular mission or missions.

operational level of warfare_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: The level of warfare at which campaigns and major operations are planned, conducted, and sustained to achieve strategic objectives within theaters or other operational areas.

operational reach_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The distance and duration across which a force can successfully employ military capabilities.

operational support airlift_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: Airlift movements of high-priority passengers and cargo with time, place, or mission-sensitive requirements.

OSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Airlift movements of high-priority passengers and cargo with time, place, or mission-sensitive requirements.

operation order_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A directive issued by a commander to subordinate commanders for the purpose of effecting the coordinated execution of an operation.

OPORD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A directive issued by a commander to subordinate commanders for the purpose of effecting the coordinated execution of an operation.

operations research_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The analytical study of military problems undertaken to provide responsible commanders and staff agencies with a scientific basis for decision on action to improve military operations. Also called operational research; operations analysis.

operations security assessment_|_dod_dic.paragraph: An evaluative process to determine the likelihood that critical information can be protected from the adversary's intelligence.

operations security indicators_|_dod_dic.paragraph: Friendly detectable actions and open-source information that can be interpreted or pieced together by an adversary to derive critical information.

operations security survey_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A collection effort by a team of subject matter experts to reproduce the intelligence image projected by a specific operation or function simulating hostile intelligence processes.

operations support element_|_dod_diction.paragraph: An element that conducts all administrative, operations support, and services support functions within the counterintelligence and human intelligence staff element of an intelligence directorate.

OSE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An element that conducts all administrative, operations support, and services support functions within the counterintelligence and human intelligence staff element of an intelligence directorate.

order of battle_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The identification, strength, command structure, and disposition of the personnel, units, and equipment of any military force. Also called OB; OOB.

organic_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Assigned to and forming an essential part of a military organization as listed in its table of organization for the Army, Air Force, and Marine Corps, and are assigned to the operating forces for the Navy.

organization for embarkation_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: In amphibious operations, an organization consisting of temporary landing force task organizations established by the commander, landing force, and a temporary organization of Navy forces established by the commander, amphibious task force, for the purpose of simplifying planning and facilitating the execution of embarkation.

OCDETF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The network of regional task forces that coordinates federal law enforcement efforts to combat the national and international organizations that cultivate, process, and distribute illicit drugs.

originator_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The command by whose authority a message is sent, which includes the responsibility for the functions of the drafter and the releasing officer.

outer transport area_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: In amphibious operations, an area inside the antisubmarine screen to which assault transports proceed initially after arrival in the objective area.

overhead persistent infrared_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: 1. Those systems originally developed to detect and track foreign intercontinental ballistic missile systems. (JP 3-14) 2. Within geospatial intelligence, a capability that provides on-demand, persistent, global, and/or localized coverage of high- to low-intensity infrared events to detect energy radiation from various tactical to strategic objects.

Overseas Environmental Baseline Guidance.paragraph: A set of objective criteria and management practices developed by the Department of Defense to protect human health and the environment.

OEBGD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A set of objective criteria and management practices developed by the Department of Defense to protect human health and the environment.

over-the-horizon amphibious operation_|_.paragraph: An operation launched from beyond visual and radar range of the shoreline.

overt operation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An operation conducted openly, without concealment. See also clandestine operation; covert operation. (JP 2-01.2) P

paramilitary forces_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Armed forces or groups distinct from the conventional armed forces of any country, but resembling them in organization, equipment, training, or mission.

partner nation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A nation that the United States works with in a specific situation or operation. (JP 1) 2. In security cooperation, a nation with which the Department of Defense conducts security cooperation activities.

PN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A nation that the United States works with in a specific situation or operation. (JP 1) 2. In security cooperation, a nation with which the Department of Defense conducts security cooperation activities.

passive defense_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Measures taken to reduce the probability of and to minimize the effects of damage caused by hostile action without the intention of taking the initiative.

patient movement_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The act or process of moving a sick, injured, wounded, or other person to obtain medical and/or dental care or treatment, which include medical regulating, patient evacuation, and en route medical care.

PM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The act or process of moving a sick, injured, wounded, or other person to obtain medical and/or dental care or treatment, which include medical regulating, patient evacuation, and en route medical care.

patient movement policy_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: Command decision establishing the maximum number of days that patients may be held within the command for treatment.

peace building_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Stability actions that strengthen and rebuild a society's institutions, infrastructure, and civic life to avoid a relapse into conflict.

PB_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Stability actions that strengthen and rebuild a society's institutions, infrastructure, and civic life to avoid a relapse into conflict.

peacekeeping_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Military operations undertaken, with the consent of all major parties to a dispute, designed to monitor and facilitate implementation of an agreement (cease fire, truce, or other such agreement) and support diplomatic efforts to reach a long-term political settlement.

peace operations_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Multiagency and multinational crisis response and limited contingency operations involving all instruments of national power with military missions to contain conflict, redress the peace, and shape the environment to support reconciliation and rebuilding and facilitate the transition to legitimate governance.

PO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Multiagency and multinational crisis response and limited contingency operations involving all instruments of national power with military missions to contain conflict, redress the peace, and shape the environment to support reconciliation and rebuilding and facilitate the transition to legitimate governance.

persistent agent_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A chemical agent that, when released, remains able to cause casualties for more than 24 hours to several days or weeks.

personal effects_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All privately owned moveable, personal property of an individual.

PE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All privately owned moveable, personal property of an individual.

personal property_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Property of any kind or any interest therein, except real property; military-issued equipment/gear; records of the United States Government; and naval vessels of the following categories: aircraft carriers, surface combatants, and submarines.

personal staff_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Aides and staff officers handling special matters over which the commander wishes to exercise close personal control.

personnel_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Individuals required in either a military or civilian capacity to accomplish the assigned mission.

personnel recovery_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The sum of military, diplomatic, and civil efforts to prepare for and execute the recovery and reintegration of isolated personnel.

PR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The sum of military, diplomatic, and civil efforts to prepare for and execute the recovery and reintegration of isolated personnel.

personnel recovery reference product_|_d.paragraph: A reference document for personnel recovery containing specific information on a particular country or region of interest.

PRRP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A reference document for personnel recovery containing specific information on a particular country or region of interest.

petroleum, oils, and lubricants_|_dod_di.paragraph: A broad term that includes all petroleum and associated products used by the Armed Forces.

POL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A broad term that includes all petroleum and associated products used by the Armed Forces.

phase line_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An easily identified feature in the operational area utilized for control and coordination of military operations.

PL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An easily identified feature in the operational area utilized for control and coordination of military operations.

physical characteristics_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: Those military characteristics of equipment that are primarily physical in nature.

physical security_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That part of security concerned with physical measures designed to safeguard personnel; to prevent unauthorized access to equipment, installations, material, and documents; and to safeguard them against espionage, sabotage, damage, and theft.

planned target_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Target that is known to exist in the operational environment, upon which actions are planned using deliberate targeting, creating effects which support commander's objectives. There are two subcategories of planned targets: scheduled and on-call. See also on-call target; operational area; scheduled target; target.

planning factor_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A multiplier used in planning to estimate the amount and type of effort involved in a contemplated operation.

planning order_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A planning directive that provides essential planning guidance and directs the development, adaptation, or refinement of a plan/order. Also called PLANORD.

planning team_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A functional element within a headquarters established to solve problems related to a specific task or requirement, and which dissolves upon completion of the assigned task.

pointee-talkee_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A language aid containing selected phrases in English opposite a translation in a foreign language used by pointing to appropriate phrases.

point of need_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In distribution operations, a physical location within a desired operational area designated by the geographic combatant commander or subordinate commander as a receiving point for forces or materiel, for subsequent use or consumption.

polar orbit_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A satellite orbit that passes over the North and South Poles on each orbit, has an angle of inclination relative to the equator of 90 degrees, and eventually passes over all points on the Earth.

port complex_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: One or more port areas in which activities are geographically linked either because these areas are dependent on a common inland transport system or because they constitute a common initial destination for convoys.

port of embarkation_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The geographic point in a routing scheme from which cargo or personnel depart.

POE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The geographic point in a routing scheme from which cargo or personnel depart.

port support activity_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A tailorable support organization composed of mobilization station assets that ensures the equipment of the deploying units is ready to load.

PSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A tailorable support organization composed of mobilization station assets that ensures the equipment of the deploying units is ready to load.

positive identification_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: An identification derived from observation and analysis of target characteristics including visual recognition, electronic support systems, non-cooperative target recognition techniques, identification friend or foe systems, or other physics-based identification techniques.

PID_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An identification derived from observation and analysis of target characteristics including visual recognition, electronic support systems, non-cooperative target recognition techniques, identification friend or foe systems, or other physics-based identification techniques.

post-launch abort_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Deliberate action taken post-separation to cause a precision munition to miss its target.

PLA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Deliberate action taken post-separation to cause a precision munition to miss its target.

precise time and time interval_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A reference value of time and time interval (frequency).

PTTI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A reference value of time and time interval (frequency).

preferred forces_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Specific units that are identified to provide assumptions essential for continued planning and assessing the feasibility of a plan.

prepare to deploy order_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: An order to a force provider to have a unit ready and to deploy within a specified response time.

PTDO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An order to a force provider to have a unit ready and to deploy within a specified response time.

pre-position_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: To place military units, equipment, or supplies at or near the point of planned use, or at a designated location, to reduce reaction time and to ensure timely support of a specific force during initial phases of an operation.

Presidential Reserve Call-up_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: Provision of a public law (Title 10, United States Code, Section 12304) that provides the President a means to activate, without a declaration of national emergency, not more than 200,000 members of the Selected Reserve and the Individual Ready Reserve (of whom not more than 30,000 may be members of the Individual Ready Reserve) for not more than 365 days to meet the requirements of any operational mission, other than for disaster relief or to suppress insurrection.

PRC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Provision of a public law (Title 10, United States Code, Section 12304) that provides the President a means to activate, without a declaration of national emergency, not more than 200,000 members of the Selected Reserve and the Individual Ready Reserve (of whom not more than 30,000 may be members of the Individual Ready Reserve) for not more than 365 days to meet the requirements of any operational mission, other than for disaster relief or to suppress insurrection.

prevention of mutual interference_|_dod_.paragraph: In submarine operations, procedures established to prevent submerged collisions between friendly submarines; between submarines and friendly, surface ship-towed bodies and arrays; and between submarines, unmanned systems, and any other hazards to submerged navigation.

PMI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In submarine operations, procedures established to prevent submerged collisions between friendly submarines; between submarines and friendly, surface ship-towed bodies and arrays; and between submarines, unmanned systems, and any other hazards to submerged navigation.

preventive medicine_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The anticipation, communication, prediction, identification, prevention, education, risk assessment, and control of communicable diseases; illnesses; and exposure to endemic, occupational, and environmental threats. Also called PVNTMED.

primary control officer_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the officer embarked in a primary control ship assigned to control the movement of landing craft, amphibious vehicles, and landing ships to and from a colored beach.

PCO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the officer embarked in a primary control ship assigned to control the movement of landing craft, amphibious vehicles, and landing ships to and from a colored beach.

primary review authority_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The organization that is assigned by the lead agent to perform the actions and coordination necessary to develop and maintain the assigned publication under the cognizance of the lead agent.

PRA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The organization that is assigned by the lead agent to perform the actions and coordination necessary to develop and maintain the assigned publication under the cognizance of the lead agent.

prime vendor_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A contracting process that provides commercial products to regionally grouped military and federal customers from commercial distributors using electronic commerce.

PV_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A contracting process that provides commercial products to regionally grouped military and federal customers from commercial distributors using electronic commerce.

principal officer_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The officer in charge of a diplomatic mission, consular office, or other foreign service post, such as a United States liaison office.

priority intelligence requirement_|_dod_.paragraph: An intelligence requirement that the commander and staff need to understand the threat and other aspects of the operational environment.

PIR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An intelligence requirement that the commander and staff need to understand the threat and other aspects of the operational environment.

private sector_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An umbrella term that may be applied to any or all of the nonpublic or commercial individuals and businesses, specified nonprofit organizations, most of academia and other scholastic institutions, and selected nongovernmental organizations.

probability of damage_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The probability that damage will occur to a target expressed as a percentage or as a decimal.

PD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The probability that damage will occur to a target expressed as a percentage or as a decimal.

procedural identification_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: An identification based on observation and analysis of target behaviors including location and trajectory, as well as compliance with airspace control measures.

procedure word_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A word or phrase limited to radio telephone procedure used to facilitate communication by conveying information in a condensed standard form.

proword_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A word or phrase limited to radio telephone procedure used to facilitate communication by conveying information in a condensed standard form.

processing and exploitation_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: In intelligence usage, the conversion of collected information into forms suitable to the production of intelligence.

procurement lead time_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The interval in time between the initiation of procurement action and receipt of the products or services purchased as the result of such actions.

production base_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The total national industrial production capacity available for the manufacture of items to meet materiel requirements.

production requirements matrix_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A compilation of prioritized combatant command all-source intelligence analysis and production requirements that support all phases of a plan.

PRMx_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A compilation of prioritized combatant command all-source intelligence analysis and production requirements that support all phases of a plan.

prompt radiation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The radiation, essentially neutrons and gamma rays, resulting from a nuclear burst and emitted from the fireball within one minute after burst.

protected emblems_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The red cross, red crescent, and other symbols that designate that persons, places, or equipment so marked have a protected status under the law of war.

protection_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Preservation of the effectiveness and survivability of mission-related military and nonmilitary personnel, equipment, facilities, information, and infrastructure deployed or located within or outside the boundaries of a given operational area.

protective clothing_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Clothing especially designed, fabricated, or treated to protect personnel against hazards.

provincial reconstruction team_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A civil-military team designated to improve stability in a given area by helping build the legitimacy and effectiveness of a host nation local or provincial government in providing security to its citizens and delivering essential government services.

PRT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A civil-military team designated to improve stability in a given area by helping build the legitimacy and effectiveness of a host nation local or provincial government in providing security to its citizens and delivering essential government services.

public affairs_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Communication activities with external and internal audiences.

PA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Communication activities with external and internal audiences.

public affairs guidance_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: Constraints and restraints established by proper authority regarding public communication activities.

PAG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Constraints and restraints established by proper authority regarding public communication activities.

Q-route_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A system of preplanned shipping lanes in mined or potentially mined waters used to minimize the area the mine countermeasures commander has to keep clear of mines in order to provide safe passage for friendly shipping.

radiation dose_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The total amount of ionizing radiation absorbed by material or tissues.

radiation exposure status_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Criteria to assist the commander in measuring unit exposure to radiation based on total past cumulative dose, normally expressed in centigray.

RES_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Criteria to assist the commander in measuring unit exposure to radiation based on total past cumulative dose, normally expressed in centigray.

radiological dispersal device_|_dod_dict.paragraph: An improvised assembly or process, other than a nuclear explosive device, designed to disseminate radioactive material to cause destruction, damage, or injury.

RDD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An improvised assembly or process, other than a nuclear explosive device, designed to disseminate radioactive material to cause destruction, damage, or injury.

radiological hazard_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Ionizing radiation that can cause damage, injury, or destruction from either external irradiation or due to radiation from radioactive materials within the body.

railhead_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A point on a railway where loads are transferred between trains and other means of transport.

rapid global mobility_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The timely movement, positioning, and sustainment of military forces and capabilities across the range of military operations.

reachback_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of obtaining products, services, and applications, or forces, or equipment, or material from organizations that are not forward deployed.
