Ready Reserve_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The Selected Reserve and Individual Ready Reserve liable for active duty as prescribed by law (Title 10, United States Code, Sections 10142, 12301, and 12302).

real property_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Lands, buildings, structures, utilities systems, improvements, and appurtenances, thereto that includes equipment attached to and made part of buildings and structures, but not movable equipment.

receiving ship_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The ship in a replenishment unit that receives the rig(s).

recognition_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The determination by any means of the individuality of persons, or of objects such as aircraft, ships, or tanks, or of phenomena such as communications-electronics patterns. 2. In ground combat operations, the determination that an object is similar within a category of something already known.

reconnaissance_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A mission undertaken to obtain, by visual observation or other detection methods, information about the activities and resources of an enemy or adversary, or to secure data concerning the meteorological, hydrographic, or geographic characteristics of a particular area.

recovery_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. In air (aviation) operations, that phase of a mission that involves the return of an aircraft to a land base or platform afloat. (JP 3-52) 2. The retrieval of a mine from the location where emplaced. (JP 3-15) 3. In personnel recovery, actions taken to physically gain custody of isolated personnel and return them to friendly control. (JP 3-50) 4. Actions taken to extricate damaged or disabled equipment for return to friendly control or repair at another location.

recovery mechanism_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An indigenous or surrogate infrastructure that is specifically developed, trained, and directed by United States forces to contact, authenticate, support, move, and exfiltrate designated isolated personnel from uncertain or hostile areas back to friendly control.

RM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An indigenous or surrogate infrastructure that is specifically developed, trained, and directed by United States forces to contact, authenticate, support, move, and exfiltrate designated isolated personnel from uncertain or hostile areas back to friendly control.

RM_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: A financial management function that provides advice and guidance to the commander to develop command resource requirements.

RM_|_dod_dictionary_def_2.paragraph: The process to identify, assess, and control risks and make decisions that balance risk cost with mission benefits.

recovery site_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In personnel recovery, an area from which isolated personnel can be recovered.

recovery vehicle_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In personnel recovery, the vehicle on which isolated personnel are boarded and transported from the recovery site.

red team_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organizational element comprised of trained and educated members that provide an independent capability to fully explore alternatives in plans and operations in the context of the operational environment and from the perspective of adversaries and others.

reduction_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The creation of lanes through a minefield or obstacle to allow passage of the attacking ground force.

regimental landing team_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A task organization for landing composed of an infantry regiment reinforced by those elements that are required for initiation of its combat function ashore.

RLT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A task organization for landing composed of an infantry regiment reinforced by those elements that are required for initiation of its combat function ashore.

regional response coordination center_|_.paragraph: A standing facility that is activated to coordinate regional response efforts until a joint field office is established and/or the principal federal official or coordinating officer can assume their National Response Framework coordination responsibilities.

RRCC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A standing facility that is activated to coordinate regional response efforts until a joint field office is established and/or the principal federal official or coordinating officer can assume their National Response Framework coordination responsibilities.

rehabilitative care_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Therapy that provides evaluations and treatment programs using exercises, massage, or electrical therapeutic treatment to restore, reinforce, or enhance motor performance and restores patients to functional health allowing for their return to duty or discharge from the Service.

restorative care_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Therapy that provides evaluations and treatment programs using exercises, massage, or electrical therapeutic treatment to restore, reinforce, or enhance motor performance and restores patients to functional health allowing for their return to duty or discharge from the Service.

reinforcing obstacles_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Those obstacles specifically constructed, emplaced, or detonated through military effort and designed to strengthen existing terrain to disrupt, fix, turn, or block enemy movement.

release altitude_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Altitude of an aircraft above the ground at the time of ordnance release.

religious advisement_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The practice of informing the commander on the impact of religion on operations, to include, but not limited to, worship, rituals, customs, and practices of United States military personnel, international forces, and the indigenous population, as well as the impact of military operations on the religious and humanitarian dynamics in the operational area.

religious discrimination_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The unlawful limits on religious expression; punishment for religious beliefs or lack of belief; or the compulsion to express opinions or beliefs contrary to religious beliefs of established religions.

religious support team_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A team comprising at least one chaplain and one enlisted religious affairs person.

RST_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A team comprising at least one chaplain and one enlisted religious affairs person.

render safe procedures_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: The portion of the explosive ordnance disposal procedures involving the application of special explosive ordnance disposal methods and tools to provide for the interruption of functions or separation of essential components of unexploded explosive ordnance to prevent an unacceptable detonation.

repair cycle_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The stages through which a repairable item passes from the time of its removal or replacement until it is reinstalled or placed in stock in a serviceable condition.

replacement in kind_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The provision of material and services for a logistic exchange of materials and services of equal value between the governments of eligible countries.

RIK_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The provision of material and services for a logistic exchange of materials and services of equal value between the governments of eligible countries.

request for assistance_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A request based on mission requirements and expressed in terms of desired outcome formally asking the Department of Defense to provide assistance within the United States or United States territories to a local, state, tribal, or other federal agency.

RFA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A request based on mission requirements and expressed in terms of desired outcome formally asking the Department of Defense to provide assistance within the United States or United States territories to a local, state, tribal, or other federal agency.

requirements approval_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The process of consolidating, validating, approving, and prioritizing contract support requests.

requirements management_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: All activities necessary to develop and approve contract support requirements, along with the associated post-contract award oversight functions, in support of combatant commander-directed operations.

rescue combat air patrol_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: An aircraft patrol provided over that portion of an objective area in which recovery operations are being conducted for the purpose of intercepting and destroying hostile aircraft.

RESCAP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An aircraft patrol provided over that portion of an objective area in which recovery operations are being conducted for the purpose of intercepting and destroying hostile aircraft.

reserve_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Portion of a body of troops that is kept to the rear or withheld from action at the beginning of an engagement to be available for a decisive movement. 2. Members of the uniformed Services who are not in active service but who are subject to call to active duty. 3. Portion of an appropriation or contract authorization held or set aside for future operations or contingencies and, in respect to which, administrative authorization to incur commitments or obligations has been withheld.

reserved obstacles_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Those demolition obstacles that are deemed critical to the plan for which the authority to detonate is reserved by the designating commander.

resettled person_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A refugee or an internally displaced person wishing to return somewhere other than his or her previous home or land within the country or area of original displacement.

residual radiation_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Nuclear radiation caused by fallout, artificial dispersion of radioactive material, or irradiation that results from a nuclear explosion and persists longer than one minute after burst.

resource management_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A financial management function that provides advice and guidance to the commander to develop command resource requirements.

restraint_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In the context of planning, a requirement placed on the command by a higher command that prohibits an action, thus restricting freedom of action. See also constraint; limitation.

restricted areas (air)_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Designated areas established by appropriate authority over which flight of aircraft is restricted.

restricted reporting_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: Reporting option that allows sexual assault victims to confidentially disclose the assault to specified individuals and receive medical treatment and counseling without triggering an official investigation.

restricted target list_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A list of restricted targets nominated by elements of the joint force and approved by the joint force commander or directed by higher authorities.

RTL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A list of restricted targets nominated by elements of the joint force and approved by the joint force commander or directed by higher authorities.

restrictive fire line_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A specific boundary established between converging, friendly surface forces that prohibits fires or their effects from crossing.

RFL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A specific boundary established between converging, friendly surface forces that prohibits fires or their effects from crossing.

resuscitative care_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Advanced emergency medical treatment required to prevent immediate loss of life or limb and to attain stabilization to ensure the patient could tolerate evacuation.

Retired Reserve_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: All reserve members who receive retirement pay on the basis of their active duty and/or reserve service; those members who are otherwise eligible for retirement pay but have not reached age 60 and who have not elected discharge and are not voluntary members of the Ready Reserve or Standby Reserve.

returnee_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A displaced person who has returned voluntarily to his or her former place of residence.

revolving fund account_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An account authorized by specific provisions of law to finance a continuing cycle of business-type operations, and which are authorized to incur obligations and expenditures that generate receipts.

rising mine_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In naval mine warfare, a mine having positive buoyancy, which is released from a sinker by a ship influence or by a timing device.

risk management_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process to identify, assess, and control risks and make decisions that balance risk cost with mission benefits.

role specialist nation_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A nation that has agreed to assume responsibility for providing a particular class of supply or service for all or part of the multinational force.

RSN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A nation that has agreed to assume responsibility for providing a particular class of supply or service for all or part of the multinational force.

roll-on/roll-off discharge facility_|_do.paragraph: A platform made up of causeway sections that provide a means of embarking and disembarking vehicles from a roll-on and roll-off ship at sea to lighterage.

RRDF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A platform made up of causeway sections that provide a means of embarking and disembarking vehicles from a roll-on and roll-off ship at sea to lighterage.

rules of engagement_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Directives issued by competent military authority that delineate the circumstances and limitations under which United States forces will initiate and/or continue combat engagement with other forces encountered.

ROE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Directives issued by competent military authority that delineate the circumstances and limitations under which United States forces will initiate and/or continue combat engagement with other forces encountered.

safe haven_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Designated area(s) to which noncombatant evacuees of the United States Government's responsibility and commercial vehicles and materiel may be evacuated during a domestic or other valid emergency. (JP 3-68) 2. A protected body of water or the well deck of an amphibious ship used by small craft operating offshore for refuge from storms or heavy seas.

salvage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Property that has some value in excess of its basic material content but is in such condition that it has no reasonable prospect of use for any purpose as a unit and its repair or rehabilitation for use as a unit is clearly impractical. 2. The saving or rescuing of condemned, discarded, or abandoned property, and of materials contained therein, for reuse, refabrication, or scrapping.

scheduled target_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Planned target upon which fires or other actions are scheduled for prosecution at a specified time.

scheme of fires_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The detailed, logical sequence of targets and fire support events to find and engage targets to support the commander's objectives.

scientific and technical intelligence_|_.paragraph: The product resulting from the collection, evaluation, analysis, and interpretation of foreign scientific and technical information that covers: a. foreign developments in basic and applied research and in applied engineering techniques; and b. scientific and technical characteristics, capabilities, and limitations of all foreign military systems, weapons, weapon systems, and materiel; the research and development related thereto; and the production methods employed for their manufacture.

S&TI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The product resulting from the collection, evaluation, analysis, and interpretation of foreign scientific and technical information that covers: a. foreign developments in basic and applied research and in applied engineering techniques; and b. scientific and technical characteristics, capabilities, and limitations of all foreign military systems, weapons, weapon systems, and materiel; the research and development related thereto; and the production methods employed for their manufacture.

sea areas_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Areas in the amphibious objective area designated for the stationing of amphibious task force ships.

seabasing_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The deployment, assembly, command, projection, reconstitution, sustainment, and re-employment of joint power from the sea without reliance on land bases within the operational area.

sea echelon_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A portion of the amphibious warfare ships or other ships that withdraws from or remains out of the transport area during an amphibious landing and operates in designated areas to seaward in an on-call or unscheduled status.

sea echelon plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, the distribution plan for amphibious shipping in the transport area to minimize losses due to enemy attack and to reduce the area to be swept of mines.

sealift enhancement features_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: Special equipment and modifications that adapt merchant-type dry cargo ships and tankers to specific military missions.

SEFs_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Special equipment and modifications that adapt merchant-type dry cargo ships and tankers to specific military missions.

seaport_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A land facility designated for reception of personnel or materiel moved by sea, and that serves as an authorized port of entrance into or departure from the country in which located.

search and rescue_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The use of aircraft, surface craft, submarines, and specialized rescue teams and equipment to search for and rescue distressed persons on land or at sea in a permissive environment.

SAR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The use of aircraft, surface craft, submarines, and specialized rescue teams and equipment to search for and rescue distressed persons on land or at sea in a permissive environment.

search and rescue point_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A predesignated specific location, relative to which isolated personnel provide their position to recovery forces.

SARDOT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A predesignated specific location, relative to which isolated personnel provide their position to recovery forces.

sea state_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A scale that categorizes the force of progressively higher seas by wave height.

section_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A subdivision of an office, installation, territory, works, or organization; especially a major subdivision of a staff.

security_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Measures taken by a military unit, activity, or installation to protect itself against all acts designed to, or which may, impair its effectiveness. (JP 3-10) 2. A condition that results from the establishment and maintenance of protective measures that ensure a state of inviolability from hostile acts or influences. (JP 3-10) 3. With respect to classified matter, the condition that prevents unauthorized persons from having access to official information that is safeguarded in the interests of national security.

security clearance_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An administrative determination by competent authority that an individual is eligible for access to classified information.

security cooperation organization_|_dod_.paragraph: A Department of Defense element that is part of the United States diplomatic mission located in a foreign country to carry out security assistance and cooperation management functions under the supervision and coordination authority of the senior defense official/defense attache.

SCO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Department of Defense element that is part of the United States diplomatic mission located in a foreign country to carry out security assistance and cooperation management functions under the supervision and coordination authority of the senior defense official/defense attache.

SCO_|_dod_dictionary_def_1.paragraph: The staff official designated by a Service head of a contracting activity to execute theater support contracting authority for a specific command and/or operational area.

security forces_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Duly constituted military, paramilitary, police, and constabulary forces of a state.

security sector reform_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A comprehensive set of programs and activities undertaken by a host nation to improve the way it provides safety, security, and justice.

SSR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A comprehensive set of programs and activities undertaken by a host nation to improve the way it provides safety, security, and justice.

segregation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In detainee operations, the removal of a detainee from other detainees and their environment for legitimate purposes unrelated to interrogation, such as when necessary for the movement, health, safety, and/or security of the detainee, the detention facility, or its personnel.

seizures_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In counterdrug operations, includes drugs and conveyances seized by law enforcement authorities and drug-related assets confiscated based on evidence that they have been derived from or used in illicit narcotics activities.

selective identification feature_|_dod_d.paragraph: A capability that, when added to the basic identification friend or foe system, provides the means to transmit, receive, and display selected coded replies.

selective off-loading_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The capability to access and off-load vehicles, supplies, and equipment without having to conduct a major reconfiguration or total off-load, which is influenced by the number and types of ships allocated and the space made available for the embarkation of the landing force.

semipermanent contingency location_|_dod.paragraph: A contingency location that provides support for a prolonged contingency operation and characterized by enhanced infrastructure and support services consistent with sustained operations.

senior contracting official_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: The staff official designated by a Service head of a contracting activity to execute theater support contracting authority for a specific command and/or operational area.

sensitive_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An agency, installation, person, position, document, material, or activity requiring special protection from disclosure that could cause embarrassment, compromise, or threat to the security of the sponsoring power.

sensitive compartmented information faci.paragraph: An accredited area, room, group of rooms, or installation where sensitive compartmented information may be stored, used, discussed, and/or electronically processed, where procedural and physical measures prevent the free access of persons unless they have been formally indoctrinated for the particular sensitive compartmented information authorized for use or storage within the sensitive compartmented information facility.

SCIF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An accredited area, room, group of rooms, or installation where sensitive compartmented information may be stored, used, discussed, and/or electronically processed, where procedural and physical measures prevent the free access of persons unless they have been formally indoctrinated for the particular sensitive compartmented information authorized for use or storage within the sensitive compartmented information facility.

serial_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. An element or a group of elements within a series that is given a numerical or alphabetical designation for convenience in planning, scheduling, and control. 2. A group of people, vehicles, equipment, or supplies used in airborne, air assault, amphibious operations, and convoys.

Service-common_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Equipment, material, supplies, and services including base operating support adopted by a Service to support its own forces and those assigned to the combatant commands.

Service-organic transportation asset_|_d.paragraph: Transportation asset that is assigned to a Military Department.

sexual assault forensic examination kit_.paragraph: The medical and forensic examination kit used to ensure controlled procedures and safekeeping of any bodily specimens in a sexual assault case.

SAFE kit_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The medical and forensic examination kit used to ensure controlled procedures and safekeeping of any bodily specimens in a sexual assault case.

sexual assault response coordinator_|_do.paragraph: The single point of contact at an installation or within a geographic area who overseas sexual assault awareness, prevention, and response.

SARC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The single point of contact at an installation or within a geographic area who overseas sexual assault awareness, prevention, and response.

shielding_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Material of suitable thickness and physical characteristics used to protect personnel from radiation during the manufacture, handling, and transportation of fissionable and radioactive materials. 2. Obstructions that tend to protect personnel or materials from the effects of a nuclear explosion.

shoot-look-shoot_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A firing doctrine in which the result of the first intercept attempt is assessed prior to the launch of a subsequent interceptor.

SLS_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A firing doctrine in which the result of the first intercept attempt is assessed prior to the launch of a subsequent interceptor.

shore party_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A task organization of the landing force, formed for the purpose of facilitating the landing and movement off the beaches of troops, equipment, and supplies; for the evacuation from the beaches of casualties and enemy prisoners of war; and for facilitating the beaching, retraction, and salvaging of landing ships and craft.

beach group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A task organization of the landing force, formed for the purpose of facilitating the landing and movement off the beaches of troops, equipment, and supplies; for the evacuation from the beaches of casualties and enemy prisoners of war; and for facilitating the beaching, retraction, and salvaging of landing ships and craft.

short-range air defense engagement zone_.paragraph: In air and missile defense, that airspace of defined dimensions within which the responsibility for engagement of air and missile threats normally rests with short-range air defense weapons, and may be established within a low- or high-altitude missile engagement zone.

SHORADEZ_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In air and missile defense, that airspace of defined dimensions within which the responsibility for engagement of air and missile threats normally rests with short-range air defense weapons, and may be established within a low- or high-altitude missile engagement zone.

show of force_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An operation planned to demonstrate United States resolve that involves increased visibility of United States deployed forces in an attempt to defuse a specific situation that, if allowed to continue, may be detrimental to United States interests or national objectives.

signals intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: 1. A category of intelligence comprising either individually or in combination all communications intelligence, electronic intelligence, and foreign instrumentation signals intelligence, however transmitted. 2. Intelligence derived from communications, electronic, and foreign instrumentation signals.

SIGINT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A category of intelligence comprising either individually or in combination all communications intelligence, electronic intelligence, and foreign instrumentation signals intelligence, however transmitted. 2. Intelligence derived from communications, electronic, and foreign instrumentation signals.

significant wave height_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The average height of the third of waves observed during a given period of time.

single-anchor leg mooring_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A mooring facility dedicated to the offshore petroleum discharge system, which permits a tanker to remain on station and pump in much higher sea states than is possible with a spread moor.

SALM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A mooring facility dedicated to the offshore petroleum discharge system, which permits a tanker to remain on station and pump in much higher sea states than is possible with a spread moor.

single-service manager_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A Service component commander who is assigned the responsibility and delegated the authority to coordinate and/or perform specified personnel support or personnel service support functions in the theater of operations.

situation report_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A report giving the situation in the area of a reporting unit or formation.

SITREP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A report giving the situation in the area of a reporting unit or formation.

sociocultural analysis_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: The analysis of adversaries and other relevant actors that integrates concepts, knowledge, and understanding of societies, populations, and other groups of people, including their activities, relationships, and perspectives across time and space at varying scales.

SCA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The analysis of adversaries and other relevant actors that integrates concepts, knowledge, and understanding of societies, populations, and other groups of people, including their activities, relationships, and perspectives across time and space at varying scales.

solatium_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Monetary compensation given in areas where it is culturally appropriate to alleviate grief, suffering, and anxiety resulting from injuries, death, and property loss with a monetary payment.

sortie allotment message_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: The means by which the joint force commander allots excess sorties to meet requirements of subordinate commanders that are expressed in their air employment and/or allocation plan.

SORTIEALOT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The means by which the joint force commander allots excess sorties to meet requirements of subordinate commanders that are expressed in their air employment and/or allocation plan.

source management_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process to register and monitor the use of sources involved in counterintelligence and human intelligence operations to protect the security of the operations and avoid conflicts among operational elements.

source zone_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In counterdrug operations, an identified geographic area for growing and/or the primary processing of the agricultural/synthetic components for illicit drugs, and where the trafficking process begins.

space assignment_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An assignment to the individual Military Departments/Services by the appropriate transportation operating agency of movement capability, which completely or partially satisfies the stated requirements of the Military Departments/Services for the operating month and that has been accepted by them without the necessity for referral to the Joint Transportation Board for allocation.

space control_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Operations to ensure freedom of action in space for the United States and its allies and deny a threat freedom of action in space.

space domain_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The area surrounding Earth at altitudes of greater than or equal to 100 kilometers above mean sea level.

space situational awareness_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: The requisite foundational, current, and predictive knowledge and characterization of space objects and the operational environment upon which space operations depend.

SSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The requisite foundational, current, and predictive knowledge and characterization of space objects and the operational environment upon which space operations depend.

space weather_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The conditions and phenomena in space and specifically in the near-Earth environment that may affect space assets or space operations.

special cargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Cargo that requires special handling or protection, such as pyrotechnics, detonators, watches, and precision instruments.

special forces group_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The largest Army combat element for special operations consisting of command and control, special forces battalions, and a support battalion capable of long-duration missions.

SFG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The largest Army combat element for special operations consisting of command and control, special forces battalions, and a support battalion capable of long-duration missions.

special mission unit_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A generic term to represent an organization composed of operations and support personnel that is task-organized to perform highly classified activities.

SMU_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A generic term to represent an organization composed of operations and support personnel that is task-organized to perform highly classified activities.

special operations command and control e.query: special operations command and control element
special operations command and control e.paragraph: A special operations element that is the focal point for the synchronization of special operations forces activities with conventional forces activities.

SOCCE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A special operations element that is the focal point for the synchronization of special operations forces activities with conventional forces activities.

special operations joint task force_|_do.paragraph: A modular, tailorable, and scalable organization composed of forces from two or more Military Departments designed to provide command and control of integrated, capable, and enabled joint special operations forces, normally commanded by a flag or general officer.

SOJTF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A modular, tailorable, and scalable organization composed of forces from two or more Military Departments designed to provide command and control of integrated, capable, and enabled joint special operations forces, normally commanded by a flag or general officer.

special operations-peculiar_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: Equipment, material, supplies, and services required for special operations missions for which there is no Service-common requirement.

special operations weather team_|_dod_di.paragraph: A task-organized team of Air Force special-tactics personnel, organized, trained, and equipped to collect critical environmental information from data-sparse areas.

SOWT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A task-organized team of Air Force special-tactics personnel, organized, trained, and equipped to collect critical environmental information from data-sparse areas.

special tactics team_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: An Air Force task-organized element of special tactics that may include combat control, pararescue, tactical air control party, and special operations weather personnel.

STT_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An Air Force task-organized element of special tactics that may include combat control, pararescue, tactical air control party, and special operations weather personnel.

specified task_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In the context of planning, a task that is specifically assigned to an organization by its higher headquarters.

spoke_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The portion of the hub and spoke distribution system that refers to transportation mode operators responsible for scheduled delivery to a customer of the "hub".

spot net_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Radio communication net used by a spotter in calling fire.

spotter_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A trained individual positioned to observe and report results of naval gunfire to the firing agency and who may also designate targets.

squadron_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. An organization consisting of two or more divisions of ships or two or more divisions (Navy) or flights of aircraft. 2. The basic administrative aviation unit of the Army, Navy, Marine Corps, and Air Force. 3. Battalion-sized ground or aviation units.

stabilized patient_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A patient whose airway is secured, hemorrhage is controlled, shock treated, and fractures are immobilized.

staff estimate_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A continual evaluation of how factors in a staff section's functional area support and impact the planning and execution of the mission.

staging_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Assembling, holding, and organizing arriving personnel, equipment, and sustaining materiel in preparation for onward movement.

staging base_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. An advanced naval base for the anchoring, fueling, and refitting of transports and cargo ships as well as replenishment of mobile service squadrons. (JP 4-01.2) 2. A landing and takeoff area with minimum servicing, supply, and shelter provided for the temporary occupancy of military aircraft during the course of movement from one location to another.

standardization_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process by which the Department of Defense achieves the closest practicable cooperation among the Services and Department of Defense agencies for the most efficient use of research, development, and production resources, and agrees to adopt on the broadest possible basis the use of: a. common or compatible operational, administrative, and logistic procedures; b. common or compatible technical procedures and criteria; c. common, compatible, or interchangeable supplies, components, weapons, or equipment; and d. common or compatible tactical doctrine with corresponding organizational compatibility.

standard use Army aircraft flight route_.query: standard use Army aircraft flight route
standard use Army aircraft flight route_.paragraph: Route established below the coordination level to facilitate the movement of Army aviation assets; it is normally located in the corps through brigade rear areas of operation and does not require approval by the airspace control authority.

SAAFR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Route established below the coordination level to facilitate the movement of Army aviation assets; it is normally located in the corps through brigade rear areas of operation and does not require approval by the airspace control authority.

standing rules for the use of force_|_do.query: standing rules for the use of force
standing rules for the use of force_|_do.paragraph: Preapproved directives to guide United States forces on the use of force during various operations.

SRUF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Preapproved directives to guide United States forces on the use of force during various operations.

station time_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In air transport operations, the time at which crews, passengers, and cargo are to be on board and ready for the flight.

sterilizer_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In mine warfare, a device included in mines to render the mine permanently inoperative on expiration of a pre-determined time after laying.

stowage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The placement of cargo into a hold or compartment or on a deck of a ship in such a way as to prevent damage from load shifts while the ship is underway.

stowage plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A completed stowage diagram showing what materiel has been loaded and its stowage location in each hold, between-deck compartment, or other space in a ship, including deck space.

strategic estimate_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The broad range of strategic factors that influence the commander's understanding of the operational environment and the determination of missions, objectives, and courses of action.

strategic intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Intelligence required for the formation of policy and military plans at national and international levels.

strategic mobility_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The capability to deploy and sustain military forces worldwide in support of national strategy.

strategic sealift shipping_|_dod_diction.paragraph: Common-user ships of the Military Sealift Command force, including pre-positioned ships after their pre-positioning mission has been completed and they have been returned to the operational control of the Military Sealift Command.

strike_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An attack to damage or destroy an objective or a capability.

structured observation management_|_dod_.paragraph: The framework for normalizing how geospatial intelligence observations from sensors and sources is captured, organized, and shared.

SOM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The framework for normalizing how geospatial intelligence observations from sensors and sources is captured, organized, and shared.

submarine operating authority_|_dod_dict.paragraph: The naval commander exercising operational control of submarines.

SUBOPAUTH_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The naval commander exercising operational control of submarines.

subordinate command_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: A command consisting of the commander and all those individuals, units, detachments, organizations, or installations that have been placed under the command by the authority establishing the subordinate command.

subsidiary landing_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: In an amphibious operation, a landing usually made outside the designated landing area.

supercargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Personnel that accompany cargo on board a ship for the purpose of accomplishing en route maintenance and security.

supply_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The procurement, distribution, maintenance while in storage, and salvage of supplies, including the determination of kind and quantity of supplies. a. producer phase-That phase of military supply that extends from determination of procurement schedules to acceptance of finished supplies by the Services. b. consumer phase-That phase of military supply that extends from receipt of finished supplies by the Services through issue for use or consumption.

supply chain risk management_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: A cross-functional approach to procuring, producing, and delivering products and services to customers.

SCRM_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A cross-functional approach to procuring, producing, and delivering products and services to customers.

support_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The action of a force that aids, protects, complements, or sustains another force in accordance with a directive requiring such action. 2. A unit that helps another unit in battle. 3. An element of a command that assists, protects, or supplies other forces in combat.

supported unit_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: As related to contracted support, an organization that is the recipient, but not necessarily the requester, of contracted support.

supporting arms coordination center_|_do.paragraph: A single location on board an amphibious warfare ship in which all communication facilities incident to the coordination of fire support of the artillery, air, and naval gunfire are centralized.

SACC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A single location on board an amphibious warfare ship in which all communication facilities incident to the coordination of fire support of the artillery, air, and naval gunfire are centralized.

supporting fire_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Fire delivered by supporting units to assist or protect a unit in combat.

supporting plan_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An operation plan prepared by a supporting commander, a subordinate commander, or an agency to satisfy the requests or requirements of the supported commander's plan. See also supported commander; supporting commander.

suppression of enemy air defenses_|_dod_.paragraph: Activity that neutralizes, destroys, or temporarily degrades surface-based enemy air defenses by destructive and/or disruptive means.

SEAD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Activity that neutralizes, destroys, or temporarily degrades surface-based enemy air defenses by destructive and/or disruptive means.

surface combatant_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A ship designed to engage in attacks against airborne, surface, subsurface, and shore targets.

surf line_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The point offshore where waves and swells are affected by the underwater surface and become breakers.

surveillance_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The systematic observation of aerospace, cyberspace, surface, or subsurface areas, places, persons, or things by visual, aural, electronic, photographic, or other means.

survival, evasion, resistance, and escap.paragraph: Actions performed by isolated personnel designed to ensure their health, mobility, safety, and honor in anticipation of or preparation for their return to friendly control.

SERE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Actions performed by isolated personnel designed to ensure their health, mobility, safety, and honor in anticipation of or preparation for their return to friendly control.

sustainment_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The provision of logistics and personnel services required to maintain and prolong operations until successful mission accomplishment.

synchronization_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. The arrangement of military actions in time, space, and purpose to produce maximum relative combat power at a decisive place and time. 2. In the intelligence context, application of intelligence sources and methods in concert with the operation plan to answer intelligence requirements in time to influence the decisions they support.

system_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A functionally, physically, and/or behaviorally related group of regularly interacting or interdependent elements; that group of elements forming a unified whole.

table of allowance_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: An equipment allowance document that prescribes basic allowances of organizational equipment and provides the control to develop, revise, or change equipment authorization inventory data.

TOA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An equipment allowance document that prescribes basic allowances of organizational equipment and provides the control to develop, revise, or change equipment authorization inventory data.

tactical air control party_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A subordinate operational component of a tactical air control system designed to provide air liaison to land forces and for the control of aircraft.

TACP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A subordinate operational component of a tactical air control system designed to provide air liaison to land forces and for the control of aircraft.

tactical air direction center_|_dod_dict.paragraph: An air operations installation, under the overall control of the Navy tactical air control center or the Marine tactical air command center, from which aircraft and air warning service functions of tactical air operations in support of amphibious operations are directed.

TADC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An air operations installation, under the overall control of the Navy tactical air control center or the Marine tactical air command center, from which aircraft and air warning service functions of tactical air operations in support of amphibious operations are directed.

tactical assembly area_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An area that is generally out of the reach of light artillery and the location where units make final preparations (pre-combat checks and inspections) and rest, prior to moving to the line of departure.

tactical combat force_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A rapidly deployable, air-ground, mobile combat unit with appropriate combat support and combat service support assets assigned to, and capable of, defeating Level III threats, including combined arms.

TCF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A rapidly deployable, air-ground, mobile combat unit with appropriate combat support and combat service support assets assigned to, and capable of, defeating Level III threats, including combined arms.

tactical data link_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: A Joint Staff-approved, standardized communication link used for the transmission of digital information via a single or multiple network architecture and multiple communication media for exchange of tactical information.

TDL_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Joint Staff-approved, standardized communication link used for the transmission of digital information via a single or multiple network architecture and multiple communication media for exchange of tactical information.

tactical intelligence_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Intelligence required for the planning and conduct of tactical operations.

tactical-logistical group_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Representatives designated by troop commanders to assist Navy control officers aboard control ships in the ship-to-shore movement of troops, equipment, and supplies.

TACLOG group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Representatives designated by troop commanders to assist Navy control officers aboard control ships in the ship-to-shore movement of troops, equipment, and supplies.

tactical obstacle_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An obstacle employed to disrupt enemy formations, to turn them into a desired area, to fix them in position under direct and indirect fires, or to block enemy penetrations.

tactical recovery of aircraft and person.query: tactical recovery of aircraft and personnel
tactical recovery of aircraft and person.paragraph: A Marine Corps mission performed by an assigned and briefed aircrew for the specific purpose of the recovery of personnel, equipment, and/or aircraft when the tactical situation precludes search and rescue assets from responding and when survivors and their location have been confirmed.

TRAP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Marine Corps mission performed by an assigned and briefed aircrew for the specific purpose of the recovery of personnel, equipment, and/or aircraft when the tactical situation precludes search and rescue assets from responding and when survivors and their location have been confirmed.

tactics_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The employment and ordered arrangement of forces in relation to each other.

target acquisition_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: The detection, identification, and location of a target in sufficient detail to permit the effective employment of capabilities that create the required effects.

TA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The detection, identification, and location of a target in sufficient detail to permit the effective employment of capabilities that create the required effects.

target area of interest_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The geographical area where high-value targets can be acquired and engaged by friendly forces.

TAI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The geographical area where high-value targets can be acquired and engaged by friendly forces.

target component_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A set of targets within a target system performing a similar function.

targeteer_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An individual who has completed requisite training and guides the joint targeting cycle in their current duties.

target folder_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A folder, hardcopy or electronic, containing target intelligence and related materials prepared for planning and executing action against a specific target.

targeting_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of selecting and prioritizing targets and matching the appropriate response to them, considering operational requirements and capabilities.

target location error_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The difference between the coordinates generated for a target and the actual location of the target.

TLE_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The difference between the coordinates generated for a target and the actual location of the target.

target nomination list_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A prioritized list of targets drawn from the joint target list, or restricted target list, and nominated by component commanders, appropriate agencies, or the joint force commander's staff for inclusion on the joint integrated prioritized target list. Also called TNL. See also candidate target list; joint integrated prioritized target list; target.

target reference point_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A predetermined point of reference, normally a permanent structure or terrain feature that can be used when describing a target location.

TRP_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A predetermined point of reference, normally a permanent structure or terrain feature that can be used when describing a target location.

target system analysis_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An all-source examination of potential target systems to determine relevance to stated objectives, military importance, and priority of attack.

TSA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An all-source examination of potential target systems to determine relevance to stated objectives, military importance, and priority of attack.

target system component_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: A related group of entities within a target system that perform or contribute toward a similar function.

task element_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A component of a naval task unit organized by the commander of a task unit or higher authority.

task group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A component of a naval task force organized by the commander of a task force or higher authority.

TG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A component of a naval task force organized by the commander of a task force or higher authority.

task organization_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organization that assigns to responsible commanders the means with which to accomplish their assigned tasks in any planned action.

tear line_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A physical line on an intelligence message or document separating categories of information that have been approved for foreign disclosure and release.

technical assistance_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The providing of advice, assistance, and training pertaining to the installation, operation, and maintenance of equipment.

technical nuclear forensics_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: The collection, analysis and evaluation of pre-detonation (intact) and post-detonation (exploded) radiological or nuclear materials, devices, and debris, as well as the immediate effects created by a nuclear detonation.

technical surveillance countermeasures_|.paragraph: Techniques to detect, neutralize, and exploit technical surveillance technologies and hazards that permit the unauthorized access to or removal of information. Also called TSCM. See also counterintelligence.

telecommunications_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Any transmission, emission, or reception of various forms of information by wire, radio, visual, or other electromagnetic systems.

temporary contingency location_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A locale that provides near-term support for a contingency operation and characterized by expedient infrastructure and support services that have been expanded beyond Service-organic capabilities.

terminal_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A facility designed to transfer cargo from one means of conveyance to another.

terminal control_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A type of air control with the authority to direct aircraft to maneuver into a position to deliver ordnance, passengers, or cargo to a specific location or target. 2. Any electronic, mechanical, or visual control given to aircraft to facilitate target acquisition and resolution.

terminal guidance operations_|_dod_dicti.paragraph: Actions using electronic, mechanical, voice, or visual communications that provide approaching aircraft and/or weapons additional information regarding a specific target location.

TGO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Actions using electronic, mechanical, voice, or visual communications that provide approaching aircraft and/or weapons additional information regarding a specific target location.

terminal phase_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: That portion of the flight of a ballistic missile that begins when the warhead or payload reenters the atmosphere and ends when the warhead or payload detonates, releases its submunitions, or impacts.

terrain analysis_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The collection, analysis, evaluation, and interpretation of geographic information on the natural and man-made features of the terrain, combined with other relevant factors, to predict the effect of the terrain on military operations.

terrain flight_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Flight close to the Earth's surface during which airspeed, height, and/or altitude are adapted to the contours and cover of the ground to avoid enemy detection and fire. Also called contour flight; low-level flight; nap-of-the-Earth flight.

terrorism threat level_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A Department of Defense intelligence threat assessment of the level of terrorist threat faced by United States personnel and interests in a foreign nation; the levels are expressed as LOW, MODERATE, SIGNIFICANT, and HIGH.

theater antisubmarine warfare commander_.paragraph: A Navy commander assigned to develop plans and direct assigned and attached assets for the conduct of antisubmarine warfare within an operational area.

TASWC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Navy commander assigned to develop plans and direct assigned and attached assets for the conduct of antisubmarine warfare within an operational area.

theater-assigned transportation assets_|.paragraph: Transportation assets that are assigned under the combatant command (command authority) of a geographic combatant commander.

theater distribution_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: The flow of personnel, equipment, and materiel within theater to meet the geographic combatant commander's missions.

TD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The flow of personnel, equipment, and materiel within theater to meet the geographic combatant commander's missions.

theater hospitalization capability_|_dod.paragraph: Essential care and health service support capabilities to either return the patient to duty and/or stabilization to ensure the patient can tolerate evacuation to a definitive care facility outside the theater, which is known as Role 3 in North Atlantic Treaty Organization doctrine.

theater of war_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Defined by the President, Secretary of Defense, or the geographic combatant commander as the area of air, land, and water that is, or may become, directly involved in the conduct of major operations and campaigns involving combat.

theater strategy_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An overarching construct outlining a combatant commander's vision for integrating and synchronizing military activities and operations with the other instruments of national power to achieve national strategic objectives.

thermal crossover_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The natural phenomenon that normally occurs twice daily when temperature conditions are such that there is a loss of contrast between two adjacent objects on infrared imagery.

third-country national_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A non-United States citizen who is working in, but not a resident of, the nation in which the United States is conducting operations.

TCN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A non-United States citizen who is working in, but not a resident of, the nation in which the United States is conducting operations.

threat analysis_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In antiterrorism, a continual process of compiling and examining all available information concerning activities by terrorist groups which could target a facility.

threat warning_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The urgent communication and acknowledgement of time-critical information essential for the preservation of life and/or vital resources.

throughput capacity_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: The estimated capacity of a port or an anchorage to clear cargo and/or passengers in 24 hours usually expressed in tons for cargo, but may be expressed in any agreed upon unit of measurement.

time of flight_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In artillery, mortar, and naval gunfire support, the time in seconds from the instant a weapon is fired, launched, or released from the delivery vehicle or weapons system to the instant it strikes or detonates.

time-phased force and deployment data_|_.paragraph: The time-phased force, non-unit cargo, and personnel data combined with movement data for the operation plan, operation order, or ongoing rotation of forces.

TPFDD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The time-phased force, non-unit cargo, and personnel data combined with movement data for the operation plan, operation order, or ongoing rotation of forces.

time-sensitive target_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: A joint force commander-validated target or set of targets requiring immediate response because it is a highly lucrative, fleeting target of opportunity or it poses (or will soon pose) a danger to friendly forces.

TST_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A joint force commander-validated target or set of targets requiring immediate response because it is a highly lucrative, fleeting target of opportunity or it poses (or will soon pose) a danger to friendly forces.

tophandler_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A device specially designed to permit the lifting and handling of containers from the top with rough terrain container handlers.

total mobilization_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Expansion of the active Armed Forces of the United States resulting from action by Congress and the President to organize and/or generate additional units or personnel beyond the existing force structure, and the resources needed for their support, to meet the total requirements of a war or other national emergency involving an external threat to the national security.

toxic industrial chemical_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: A chemical developed or manufactured for use in industrial operations or research by industry, government, or academia that poses a hazard.

TIC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A chemical developed or manufactured for use in industrial operations or research by industry, government, or academia that poses a hazard.

toxic industrial radiological_|_dod_dict.paragraph: Any radiological material manufactured, used, transported, or stored by industrial, medical, or commercial processes.

TIR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any radiological material manufactured, used, transported, or stored by industrial, medical, or commercial processes.

track correlation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Correlating track information for identification purposes using all available data.

track management_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Defined set of procedures whereby the commander ensures accurate friendly and enemy unit and/or platform locations and a dissemination procedure for filtering, combining, and passing that information to higher, adjacent, and subordinate commanders.

tradecraft_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Specialized methods and equipment used in the organization and activity of intelligence organizations, especially techniques and methods for handling communications with agents. 2. Operational practices and skills used in the performance of intelligence related duties.

training aid_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Any item developed or procured with the primary intent that it shall assist in training and the process of learning.

transient forces_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Forces that pass or stage through, or base temporarily within, the operational area of another command but are not under its operational control.

transmission security_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: Actions designed to protect communications from interception and exploitation by means other than cryptoanalysis.

TRANSEC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Actions designed to protect communications from interception and exploitation by means other than cryptoanalysis.

transport area_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: In amphibious operations, an area assigned to a transport organization for the purpose of debarking troops and equipment.

transportation feasibility_|_dod_diction.paragraph: A determination that the available lift capability exists to move forces, equipment, and supplies from the point of origin to the port of debarkation within the commander's timeline.

transportation priorities_|_dod_dictiona.paragraph: Indicators assigned to eligible traffic that establish its movement precedence.

transport group_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An element that directly deploys and supports the landing of the landing force and is functionally designated as a transport group in the amphibious task force organization.

troop space cargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Cargo, such as sea or barracks bags, bedding rolls or hammocks, locker trunks, and office equipment, normally stowed in an accessible place, as well as normal hand-carried combat equipment and weapons to be carried ashore by the assault troops.

turning movement_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A variation of the envelopment in which the attacking force passes around or over the enemy's principal defensive positions to secure objectives deep in the enemy's rear to force the enemy to abandon his position or divert major forces to meet the threat. (JP 3-06) U

unauthorized commitment_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: An agreement that is not binding solely because the United States Government representative who made it lacked the authority to enter into that agreement on behalf of the United States Government.

unconventional assisted recovery_|_dod_d.paragraph: Nonconventional assisted recovery conducted by special operations forces.

UAR_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Nonconventional assisted recovery conducted by special operations forces.

unconventional warfare_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: Activities conducted to enable a resistance movement or insurgency to coerce, disrupt, or overthrow a government or occupying power by operating through or with an underground, auxiliary, and guerrilla force in a denied area.

UW_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Activities conducted to enable a resistance movement or insurgency to coerce, disrupt, or overthrow a government or occupying power by operating through or with an underground, auxiliary, and guerrilla force in a denied area.

underwater demolition_|_dod_dictionary_d.paragraph: The destruction or neutralization of underwater obstacles that is normally accomplished by underwater demolition teams.

unexploded explosive ordnance_|_dod_dict.paragraph: Explosive ordnance that has been primed, fused, armed or otherwise prepared for action, and that has been fired, dropped, launched, projected, or placed in such a manner as to constitute a hazard to operations, installations, personnel, or material and remains unexploded either by malfunction or design or for any other cause.

UXO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Explosive ordnance that has been primed, fused, armed or otherwise prepared for action, and that has been fired, dropped, launched, projected, or placed in such a manner as to constitute a hazard to operations, installations, personnel, or material and remains unexploded either by malfunction or design or for any other cause.

unified command_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A command with a broad continuing mission under a single commander and composed of significant assigned components of two or more Military Departments that is established and so designated by the President, through the Secretary of Defense with the advice and assistance of the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.

unified geospatial-intelligence operatio.paragraph: The collaborative and coordinated process to assess, align, and execute geospatial intelligence across the National System for Geospatial Intelligence and its partner organizations.

UGO_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The collaborative and coordinated process to assess, align, and execute geospatial intelligence across the National System for Geospatial Intelligence and its partner organizations.

unit_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. Any military element whose structure is prescribed by competent authority. 2. An organization title of a subdivision of a group in a task force.

United States_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Includes the land area, internal waters, territorial sea, and airspace of the United States, including a. United States territories; and b. Other areas over which the United States Government has complete jurisdiction and control or has exclusive authority or defense responsibility.

United States message text format_|_dod_.paragraph: A program designed to enhance joint and combined combat effectiveness through standardization of message formats, data elements, and information exchange procedures.

USMTF_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A program designed to enhance joint and combined combat effectiveness through standardization of message formats, data elements, and information exchange procedures.

United States person_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A United States citizen; an alien known by the concerned intelligence agency to be a permanent resident alien; an unincorporated association substantially composed of United States citizens or permanent resident aliens; or a corporation incorporated in the United States, except for those directed and controlled by a foreign government or governments.

unit line number_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A seven-character alphanumeric code that describes a unique increment of a unit deployment, i.e., advance party, main body, equipment by sea and air, reception team, or trail party, in the time-phased force and deployment data.

ULN_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A seven-character alphanumeric code that describes a unique increment of a unit deployment, i.e., advance party, main body, equipment by sea and air, reception team, or trail party, in the time-phased force and deployment data.

unit type code_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Joint Chiefs of Staff-developed and -assigned code, consisting of five characters that uniquely identify a "type unit."

UTC_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A Joint Chiefs of Staff-developed and -assigned code, consisting of five characters that uniquely identify a "type unit."

unity of effort_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Coordination and cooperation toward common objectives, even if the participants are not necessarily part of the same command or organization, which is the product of successful unified action.

Universal Time_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A measure of time that conforms, within a close approximation, to the mean diurnal rotation of the Earth and serves as the basis of civil timekeeping.

ZULU time_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A measure of time that conforms, within a close approximation, to the mean diurnal rotation of the Earth and serves as the basis of civil timekeeping.

unmanned aircraft_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An aircraft that does not carry a human operator and is capable of flight with or without human remote control.

UA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An aircraft that does not carry a human operator and is capable of flight with or without human remote control.

unrestricted reporting_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: A process that a Service member uses to disclose, without requesting confidentiality or restricted reporting, that he or she is the victim of a sexual assault.

unstable patient_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A patient whose physiological status is in fluctuation and for whom emergent, treatment, and/or surgical intervention are anticipated during treatment or evacuation, and the patient's rapidly changing status and requirements are beyond the standard en route care capability and requires medical/surgical augmentation.

use of force policy_|_dod_dictionary_def.paragraph: Policy guidance issued by the Commandant, United States Coast Guard, on the use of force and weapons. (JP 3-03) V

validation_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A process associated with the collection and production of intelligence that confirms that an intelligence collection or production requirement is sufficiently important to justify the dedication of intelligence resources, does not duplicate an existing requirement, and has not been previously satisfied. (JP 2-01) 2. A part of target development that ensures all candidate targets meet the objectives and criteria outlined in the commander's guidance and ensures compliance with the law of war and rules of engagement. (JP 3-60) 3. In the context of time-phased force and deployment data validation, it is an execution procedure whereby all the information records in the time-phased force and deployment data are confirmed error-free and accurately reflect the current status, attributes, and availability of units and requirements. (JP 3-35) 4. A global force management procedure for assessing combatant command requirements to determine viability, for sourcing, with respect to risk and prioritization between competing needs and the nature of the requirement.

vehicle cargo_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Wheeled or tracked equipment, including weapons, that require certain deck space, head room, and other definite clearance.

vertical stowage_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A method of stowage in depth within a single compartment by which loaded items are continually accessible for unloading and the unloading can be completed without corresponding changes or prior unloading of other cargo.

visual information_|_dod_dictionary_def_.paragraph: Various visual media with or without sound that generally includes still and motion photography, audio video recording, graphic arts, and visual presentations.

VI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Various visual media with or without sound that generally includes still and motion photography, audio video recording, graphic arts, and visual presentations.

voluntary tanker agreement_|_dod_diction.paragraph: An agreement established by the Maritime Administration to provide for United States commercial tanker owners and operators to voluntarily make their vessels available to satisfy the Department of Defense to meet contingency or war requirements for point-to-point petroleum, oils, and lubricants movements.

VTA_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An agreement established by the Maritime Administration to provide for United States commercial tanker owners and operators to voluntarily make their vessels available to satisfy the Department of Defense to meet contingency or war requirements for point-to-point petroleum, oils, and lubricants movements.

vulnerability assessment_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: A Department of Defense, command, or unit-level evaluation to determine the vulnerability of an installation, unit, exercise, port, ship, residence, facility, or other site to a physical or cyberspace threat. (JP 3-26) W

warden system_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An informal method of communication used to pass information to United States citizens living in affected areas overseas during emergencies.

warning order_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A preliminary notice of an order or action that is to follow. 2. A planning directive that initiates the development and evaluation of military courses of action by a commander.

WARNORD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: 1. A preliminary notice of an order or action that is to follow. 2. A planning directive that initiates the development and evaluation of military courses of action by a commander.

Washington Liaison Group_|_dod_dictionar.paragraph: An organization consisting of members of Department of State and Department of Defense, chaired by a representative of Department of State, which has basic responsibility for the coordination and implementation of plans for the protection and evacuation in emergencies of persons abroad for whom the Secretaries of State or Defense are responsible.

WLG_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: An organization consisting of members of Department of State and Department of Defense, chaired by a representative of Department of State, which has basic responsibility for the coordination and implementation of plans for the protection and evacuation in emergencies of persons abroad for whom the Secretaries of State or Defense are responsible.

wave_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A formation of forces, including landing craft, amphibious vehicles, or aircraft, required to beach or land about the same time.

weaponeering_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: The process of determining the specific means required to create a desired effect on a given target.

weapons control status_|_dod_dictionary_.paragraph: An air and missile defense control measure declared for a particular area and time by an area air defense commander, or delegated subordinate commander, based on the rules of engagement that establish the conditions under which fighters and surface air defense weapons are permitted to engage threats. Also call WCS.

weapons of mass destruction_|_dod_dictio.paragraph: Chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear weapons capable of a high order of destruction or causing mass casualties, excluding the means of transporting or propelling the weapon where such means is a separable and divisible part from the weapon.

WMD_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Chemical, biological, radiological, or nuclear weapons capable of a high order of destruction or causing mass casualties, excluding the means of transporting or propelling the weapon where such means is a separable and divisible part from the weapon.

weapons readiness state_|_dod_dictionary.paragraph: The degree of readiness of air defense weapons which can become airborne or be launched to carry out an assigned task, and normally expressed in numbers of weapons and numbers of minutes.

weapons technical intelligence_|_dod_dic.paragraph: A subcategory of technical intelligence derived from the technical and forensic collection and exploitation of improvised explosive devices, associated components, improvised weapons, and other systems.

WTI_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A subcategory of technical intelligence derived from the technical and forensic collection and exploitation of improvised explosive devices, associated components, improvised weapons, and other systems.

wellness_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: Force health protection program that consolidates and incorporates physical and mental fitness, health promotion, and environmental and occupational health.

witting_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A term of intelligence art that indicates that one is not only aware of a fact or piece of information but also aware of its connection to intelligence activities.

working capital fund_|_dod_dictionary_de.paragraph: A revolving fund established to finance inventories of supplies and other stores, or to provide working capital for industrial-type activities.

zone of action_|_dod_dictionary_def_0.paragraph: A tactical subdivision of a larger area.
